{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 1}Now there was a certain man of Ramah, a Zuphite of the hill country of Ephraim, and his name was Elkanah the son of Jeroham, the son of Elihu, the son of Tohu, the son of Zuph, an Ephraimite. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}He had two wives: the name of the one was Hannah, and the name of the other Peninnah. Peninnah had children, but Hannah had none. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}This man used to go up from his city year by year to worship and to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord} of armies in Shiloh. Eli and his two sons, Hophni and Phinehas, were priests to the {\scaps Lord} there. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}It came to pass on one occasion that Elkanah sacrificed. Now he used to give portions to Peninnah his wife and to all her sons and daughters, {\super\cf2\fs24 5}but to Hannah he used to give a double portion because he loved her. But the {\scaps Lord} had shut up her womb. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Her rival used to vex her bitterly in order to make her angry, because the {\scaps Lord} had shut up her womb. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}This happened year after year, as often as she went up to the house of the {\scaps Lord}, she used to vex her; therefore she wept and would not eat. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}But Elkanah her husband said to her, \uc1\u8220*Hannah, why do you weep and not eat, and why is your heart sad? Am not I better to you than ten sons?\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}So Hannah rose up, after they had eaten in Shiloh, and stood before the {\scaps Lord}. Now Eli the priest was sitting at his seat at the door-posts of the temple of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}She was greatly distressed and prayed fervently to the {\scaps Lord} and wept bitterly. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}She vowed a vow, saying,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*O {\scaps Lord} of armies!
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
If you will indeed look on the affliction of your maid-servant,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
remember me and not forget your maid-servant,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
but will give to your maid-servant a boy
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
then I will give him to the {\scaps Lord} all the days of his life.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
A razor will not come upon his head.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}While she continued praying before the {\scaps Lord}, Eli observed her mouth. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Now Hannah was speaking to herself. Only her lips moved, but her voice was not heard; therefore Eli took her for a drunken woman. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}So Eli said to her, \uc1\u8220*How long will you act like a drunken woman? Put away the effects of your wine and go from the presence of the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}\uc1\u8220*No, my lord,\uc1\u8221* Hannah answered, \uc1\u8220*I am an unfortunate woman! I have drunk neither wine nor intoxicating drink, but I have been pouring out my heart before the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Do not take your maid-servant to be a vile woman, for because of the greatness of my grief and vexation have I continued speaking until now.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Then Eli answered, \uc1\u8220*Go in peace, and the God of Israel grant your petition that you have asked of him.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 18}She said, \uc1\u8220*Let your maid-servant find favor in your sight.\uc1\u8221* So the woman went her way and ate, and her face was no longer sad.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}They rose up in the morning early, and worshipped before the {\scaps Lord}, and returned and came to their house at Ramah. And Elkanah knew Hannah his wife; and the {\scaps Lord} remembered her.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}And Hannah conceived, and it came to pass at the coming around of the new year that she bore a son, and named him Samuel{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn   Heb: Asked of God }, saying, \uc1\u8220*For I have asked him of the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 21}The man Elkanah and all his household went up to offer to the {\scaps Lord} the yearly sacrifice and his vow. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}But Hannah did not go up; for she said to her husband, \uc1\u8220*When the child is weaned then I will bring him and he will appear in the presence of the {\scaps Lord} and will live there forever.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Elkanah her husband said to her, \uc1\u8220*Do what seems good to you: wait until you have weaned him; only may the {\scaps Lord} establish your word.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
So the woman waited and nursed her son until she weaned him. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}When she had weaned him, she took him up with her, together with a three-year-old bullock and a bushel of flour and a skin of wine, and brought him to the house of the {\scaps Lord} in Shiloh. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}They slew the bullock and Hannah brought the lad to Eli. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}She said, \uc1\u8220*Oh, sir, by your life, I am the woman who stood near you here, praying fervently to the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 27}This is the lad regarding whom I was fervently praying, and the {\scaps Lord} has granted me my petition which I asked of him. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Now, I on my part have given him to the {\scaps Lord}; as long as he lives he is given to the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221* So she left him there before the {\scaps Lord}. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 2}And Hannah prayed:
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\cf2\fs24 1}My heart exults in the {\scaps Lord},
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
my strength is exalted in the {\scaps Lord};
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
my mouth laughs at my enemies;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
because I rejoice in your salvation.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 2}There is none holy as the {\scaps Lord},
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
there is none like you;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
there is no rock like our God.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Do not talk so proudly,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
let not arrogance come out of your mouth,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
for the {\scaps Lord} is a God of knowledge,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
and by him actions are weighed.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}The bows of the mighty men are broken,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
and they that stumbled are girded with strength.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}They that were full have hired out themselves for bread,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
and they that were hungry have ceased;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
while the barren has borne seven,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
she who had many children has languished.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}The {\scaps Lord} kills, and makes alive;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
he brings down to the grave, and brings up.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The {\scaps Lord} makes poor, and makes rich;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
he brings low, he also lifts up.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}He raises up the poor out of the dust,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
he lifts up the needy from the garbage heap
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
to make them sit with princes,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
and inherit the throne of glory.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
For the pillars of the earth are the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
and he has set the world upon them.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}He will guard the feet of his holy ones,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
but the wicked will be put to silence in darkness;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
for not by strength will humans prevail.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}They who strive with the {\scaps Lord} will be broken to pieces;
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
against them will he thunder in heaven.
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
The {\scaps Lord} will judge the ends of the earth,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
he will give strength to his king
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
and exalt the power of his anointed.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}So Elkanah went to Ramah. But the lad was ministering to the {\scaps Lord} in the presence of Eli the priest. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Now the sons of Eli were base scoundrels; they had no regard for the {\scaps Lord}, {\super\cf2\fs24 13}nor for what was justly due to the priest from the people. Whenever a man offered a sacrifice, the priest\uc1\u8217*s servant would come, while the meat was boiling, with a three-pronged fork in his hand, {\super\cf2\fs24 14}and would strike into the pot or the kettle or the basin or the dish. All that the fork brought up the priest would take for himself. So they did to all the Israelites who came to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord} in Shiloh. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Moreover before they burned the fat, the priest\uc1\u8217*s servant used to come and say to the man who was making the offering, \uc1\u8220*Give me meat to roast for the priest; for he will not take from you boiled flesh, but raw.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Should the man, however, say to him, \uc1\u8220*First you should burn the fat, then take as much as you desire,\uc1\u8221* he would reply, \uc1\u8220*No, you must give it at once or else I will take it by force.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}The sin of the young men was very great before the {\scaps Lord}, for the men had contempt for the offering of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}And Samuel continued ministering before the {\scaps Lord} \uc1\u8211* a lad girded with a linen ephod. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}His mother used to make him a little robe and bring it to him from year to year, when she came up with her husband to offer the yearly sacrifice. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}And Eli would bless Elkanah and his wife and say, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord} repay you with offspring from this woman for the gift which she gave to the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221* Then they would return to their own home. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}And the {\scaps Lord} visited Hannah so that she conceived and bore three sons and two daughters. The child Samuel grew up before the {\scaps Lord}.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Now Eli was very old; and whenver he heard what his sons were doing to all Israel, how they lay with the women who did service at the door of the tent of meeting, {\super\cf2\fs24 23}he said to them, \uc1\u8220*Why do you do such things as these, which I hear from the mouth of all the people. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}No, my sons; for it is no good report that I hear the people of the {\scaps Lord} spreading abroad. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}If one man sin against another, God will mediate for him; but if a man sin against the {\scaps Lord}, who could act as mediator for him?\uc1\u8221* Notwithstanding they did not listen to the voice of their father, because the {\scaps Lord} desired to slay them. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}But the lad Samuel kept on growing larger and better in the estimation both of the {\scaps Lord} and of men.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 27}There came a man of God to Eli and said to him, \uc1\u8220*This is the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s message: I revealed myself to your father\uc1\u8217*s house, when they were in Egypt servants to Pharaoh\uc1\u8217*s house, {\super\cf2\fs24 28}and I chose him from all the tribes of Israel to be my priest to go up to my altar to burn sacrifices, to bear an ephod before me, and I gave to your father\uc1\u8217*s house for food all the offerings of the Israelites made by fire. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Why do you look with envious eyes on my sacrifices and offerings, and honor your sons above me in fattening yourselves with the first-fruits of all the offerings which the Israelites bring me?\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 30}Therefore the {\scaps Lord} the God of Israel says, \uc1\u8216*I had indeed thought that your house and the house of your father would walk before me forever,\uc1\u8217* but now the {\scaps Lord} says, \uc1\u8216*Far be it from me, for them who honor me I will honor, and they who despise me will be lightly esteemed. {\super\cf2\fs24 31}The days are quickly coming when I Will cut off your arm and the arm of your father\uc1\u8217*s house. {\super\cf2\fs24 32}You will look in affliction and enviously on all the prosperity which I will give Israel, and there will not be an old man in your house forever. {\super\cf2\fs24 33}The only one of you whom I do not cut off from my altar will be spared to weep out his eyes and to wear out his body, and all of your household will die by the sword of men. {\super\cf2\fs24 34}This will be the sign to you that will come upon your two sons, Hophni and Phinehas: on the same day both will die. {\super\cf2\fs24 35}And I will raise up for myself a faithful priest who will do according to that which is in my heart and in my desire, and I will build him an enduring house, and he will walk before my anointed forever. {\super\cf2\fs24 36}Anyone who is left in your house will come to do him obeisance for a piece of money or a loaf of bread, and will beg to be given in one of the priests\uc1\u8217* offices so that they may eat a morsel of bread.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 3}The child Samuel continued ministering before the {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} in the presence of Eli. The word of the {\scaps Lord} was rare in those days; there were no frequent visions. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Once at that time, when Eli was lying in his Samuel place \uc1\u8211* his eyes had begun to grow dim, so that he could not see \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}and while the lamp of God was still burning, and Samuel was lying in the temple of the {\scaps Lord} where the ark of God was, {\super\cf2\fs24 4}the {\scaps Lord} called, \uc1\u8220*Samuel! Samuel!\uc1\u8221* He said, \uc1\u8220*Here I am.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}He ran to Eli, and said, \uc1\u8220*Here I am; you called me.\uc1\u8221* But he said, \uc1\u8220*I didn\uc1\u8217*t call, lie down again.\uc1\u8221* So he went and lay down. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Then the {\scaps Lord} called yet again, \uc1\u8220*Samuel! Samuel!\uc1\u8221* And Samuel arose and went to Eli and said, \uc1\u8220*Here I am; you called me.\uc1\u8221* But he answered, \uc1\u8220*I didn\uc1\u8217*t call, my son. Lie down again.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Now Samuel did not yet know the {\scaps Lord} neither had the word of the {\scaps Lord} yet been revealed to him. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}So when the {\scaps Lord} called Samuel again the third time, he arose and went to Eli, and said, \uc1\u8220*Here I am; for you called me.\uc1\u8221* Then Eli realized that the {\scaps Lord} was calling the child. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}So Eli said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Go, lie down; and if you are called, say, \uc1\u8216*Speak, {\scaps Lord}, for your servant is listening.\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217* So Samuel went and lay down in his place. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then the {\scaps Lord} came, and stood there, and called as at other times, \uc1\u8220*Samuel! Samuel!\uc1\u8221* And Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*Speak; for your servant is listening.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}And the {\scaps Lord} said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*See, I am about to do such a thing in Israel, that the ears of everyone who hears it will ring. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}In that day I will perform toward Eli all that I have spoken against his house from beginning to end. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}For I have told him that I will judge his house forever, for the guilt which he knew, in that his sons were blaspheming God and he did not restrain them. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Therefore I have sworn to the house of Eli that the guilt of Eli\uc1\u8217*s house will not be expiated with sacrifice nor offering forever.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}And Samuel lay there until the morning. Then he rose early in the morning and opened the doors of the house of the {\scaps Lord}. Samuel was afraid to make the known the vision to Eli. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}But Eli called Samuel and said, \uc1\u8220*Samuel, my son.\uc1\u8221* He said, \uc1\u8220*I am here.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}He said, \uc1\u8220*What is the thing that the {\scaps Lord} has spoken to you? Hide nothing from me. May God do to you whatever he will, if you conceal from me a word of all that he spoke to you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}So Samuel told him everything; and hid nothing from him. And Eli said, \uc1\u8220*It is the {\scaps Lord}; let him do what seems good to him.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}And Samuel grew, and the {\scaps Lord} was with him and let none of his words fall to the ground. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}All Israel from Dan even to Beersheba knew that Samuel was established as a prophet of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}And the {\scaps Lord} again appeared in Shiloh, for the {\scaps Lord} revealed himself to Samuel,  {\cf1 4}and the word of Samuel came to all Israel.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Samuel the judge

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
{\super\cf2\fs24 1}Now in those days the Philistines assembled to make war against Israel. Israel went out against the Philistines to battle, and encamped at Ebenezer; and the Philistines encamped in Aphek. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}The Philistines put themselves in array against Israel, and Israel was smitten before the Philistines, and the battle was hard fought and they slew in the ranks on the field about four thousand men. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}But when the people returned to the camp, the elders of Israel said, \uc1\u8220*Why has the {\scaps Lord} smitten us today before the Philistines? Let us bring to us the ark of our God out of Shiloh, that it may come among us and save us from the hand of our enemies.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So they sent to Shiloh; and took from there the ark of the {\scaps Lord} of armies who sits enthroned above the cherubim. The two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas, were there with the ark of God. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}When the ark of God the {\scaps Lord} came to the camp, all Israel shouted such a great shout that the earth rang.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}When the Philistines heard the noise of the shout, they said, \uc1\u8220*What does this great shouting in the Hebrew\uc1\u8217*s camp mean?\uc1\u8221* When they learned that the ark of the {\scaps Lord} had come to the camp, {\super\cf2\fs24 7}they were afraid, and said, \uc1\u8220*These are their gods. They have come to them to the camp. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Woe to Woe to us! Nothin like this has happened to us before! Who can deliver us out of the hand of these mighty gods? These are the gods who smote the Egyptians with every sort of plague and pesilence. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Be strong, and be men, O Philistines, so that you will not become slaves to the Hebrews, as they have been slaves to you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}So the Philistines fought and there was great slaughter. Israel was defeated and each fled to his home. There fell of Israel thirty thousand footmen. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}The ark of God was taken, and the two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas, perished.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}A Benjamite ran from the ranks and came to Shiloh the same day with his garments torn and with earth on his head. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Just as he came, Eli was sitting upon his seat beside the gate watching the road, for his heart was trembling for the ark of God. When the man came to the city to inform it, all the city cried out. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}When Eli heard the noise of the crying he said, \uc1\u8220*What is this tumultuous noise?\uc1\u8221* The man came quickly and told Eli. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}(Now Eli was ninety-eight years old, and his eyes were set, so that he could not see). {\super\cf2\fs24 16}The man said to Eli, \uc1\u8220*I have come from the battle, for I fled today from the ranks.\uc1\u8221* He said, \uc1\u8220*How went the matter, my son?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}He that brought the tidings answered, \uc1\u8220*Israel fled before the Philistines, and there was also a great slaughter among the people, and your two sons also, Hophni and Phinehas, are dead, and the ark of God has been captured.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}When he mentioned the ark of God, Eli fell from his seat backward by the side of the gate; and his neck was broken and he died, for he was old and heavy. He had judged Israel forty years.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}His daughter-in-law, Phinehas\uc1\u8217*s wife, was pregnant and near her time. When she heard the report regarding the capture of the ark of God, and that her father-in-law and her husband were dead, she went into labor and crouched down and gave birth to a child. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}As she lay dying, the women who stood by her said to her, \uc1\u8220*Do not fear, for you have given birth to a son.\uc1\u8221* But she neither answered nor heeded. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}She named the child Ichabod, saying, \uc1\u8220*The glory is taken away from Israel,\uc1\u8221* meaning the capture of the ark of God, and the deaths of her father-in-law and her husband. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}\uc1\u8220*Glory has left Israel,\uc1\u8221* she said, \uc1\u8220*because the ark of God is taken.\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 5}The Philistines took the ark of God and brought it from Ebenezer to Ashdod. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Then the Philistines took the ark of the {\scaps Lord} and brought it to the house of Dagon and set it up by the side of Dagon. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}When the Ashdodites arose early the next day, there was Dagon fallen upon his face to the ground before the ark of the {\scaps Lord}. They raised up Dagon and set him in his place again. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}But when they arose early on the following morning, behold there was Dagon fallen upon his face to the ground before the ark of the {\scaps Lord}. The head of Dagon and both his hands were cut off upon the threshold, and only the body of Dagon was left. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}This is why the priests of Dagon and all who enter the house of Dagon do not tread on the threshold of Dagon in Ashdod to this day, but step over it. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}The hand of the {\scaps Lord} was heavy upon the Ashdodites, and he destroyed them, and struck them with tumors, both in Ashdod and its borders. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}When the men of Ashdod saw that it was so, they said, \uc1\u8220*The ark of the God of Israel must not remain with us, for his hand is severe on us and on Dagon our god.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 8}So they sent and gathered together all the lords of the Philistines, and said, \uc1\u8220*What should we do with the ark of the God of Israel?\uc1\u8221* They answered, \uc1\u8220*Let the ark of the God of Israel be brought around to Gath.\uc1\u8221* So they moved the ark of the God of Israel to Gath. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}But after they had brought it to Gath, the hand of the {\scaps Lord} was against the city \uc1\u8211* there was a very great panic \uc1\u8211* and he struck the men of the city, both young and old, so that tomors broke out on them. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}So they sent the ark of God to Ekron. But when the ark of God came to Ekron, the Ekronites cried out, \uc1\u8220*They have brought around the ark of the God of Israel to us, to slay us and our people.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}They sent therefore and gathered together all the lords of the Philistines and said, \uc1\u8220*Send away the ark of the God of Israel, let it go back to its own place and not kill us and our people.\uc1\u8221* For a deadly panic had seized the entire city. The hand of God was very heavy there. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}The men who did not die were stricken with the tumors, and the cry of lamentation from the city went up to heaven. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 6}The ark of the {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} was in the country of the Philistines for seven months. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Then the Philistines summoned the priests and the diviners, and said, \uc1\u8220*What should we do with the ark of the {\scaps Lord}? Show us how we should send it to its place.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}They said, \uc1\u8220*If you are sending the ark of the God of Israel, you must not send it away empty. You must return to him a guilt offering. Then you will be healed and it will be made known to you why his hand is not removed from you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Then they were asked, \uc1\u8220*What should the guilt offering be which we should return to him?\uc1\u8221* and they said, \uc1\u8220*Five golden tumors, and five golden rats, corresponding to the number of the lords of the Philistines; for one plague was upon you as well as upon your lords. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Therefore you should make images of your tumors, and images of your rats that ravage the land, and you should give glory to the God of Israel. Perhaps he will lighten his hand from on you and your gods and your land. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Why be stubborn, as the Egyptians and Pharaoh were stubborn? Remember how he made sport of them until they let Israel go?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}So take and prepare a new cart, and two milch cows which have never been yoked, and fasten the cows to the cart. But leave their calves behind them at home. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Take the ark of the {\scaps Lord} and place it on the cart and put the golden objects which you are returning to him as a guilt offering in a box at its side. Then send it on its way. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Watch; if it goes on the way to its own land, to Beth-shemesh, then it was the {\scaps Lord} was did us this great harm, but if not, then we will know that it was not his hand that stuck us but it was an accident that happened to us.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}The men did all this. They took two mulch cows and fastened them to the cart, and shut up their calves at home. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}They placed the ark of the {\scaps Lord} on the cart, and the box with the golden rats and the images of their tumors. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}The cows took a straight course in the direction of Beth-shemesh. They went along the highway, lowing as they went, and did not turn left nor right. The lords of the Philistines went after them to the border of Beth-shemesh. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}The inhabitants of Beth-shemesh were harvesting their wheat in the valley. They lifted up their eyes and saw the ark, and came rejoicing to meet it. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}When the cart came into the field of Joshua of Beth-shemesh, it stood still there, near a great stone. So they chopped up the wood of the cart and offered the cows as a burnt offering to the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}The Levites took down the ark of the {\scaps Lord} and the box that was with it, in which were the golden objects, and placed them on the great stone. The men of Beth-shemesh offered to the {\scaps Lord} on that day burnt offerings and ordinary sacrifices. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}When the five lords of the Philistines saw it, they returned to Ekron on that day.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}These are the golden tumors which the Philistines returned as a guilt offering to the {\scaps Lord}: one for Ashdod, one for Gaza, one for Ashkelon, one for Gath, and one for Ekron. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}The golden rats correspond to the number of all the cities of the Philistines belonging to the five lords, both of fortified cities and of country villages. A witness is the great stone, by which they set down the ark of the {\scaps Lord}. To this day it is in the field of Joshua of Beth-shemesh.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}The descendents of Jechoniah, however, did not rejoice with the men of Beth-shemesh, when they welcomed the ark of the {\scaps Lord}. So he killed seventy of them, and the people mourned because the {\scaps Lord} had struck the people with such a great slaughter. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}The people of Beth-shemesh said, \uc1\u8220*Who is able to stand before the {\scaps Lord}, this holy God? To whom can we send him to be rid of him?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 21}So they sent messengers to the inhabitants of Kiriath-jearim, saying, \uc1\u8220*The Philistines have brought back the ark of the {\scaps Lord}. Come and take it back with you.\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 7}So the people of Kiriath-jearim came, and took the ark of the {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord}, and carried it into the house of Abinadab on the hill, and consecrated Eleazar, his son, to guard the ark of the {\scaps Lord}.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Many years passed from the time the ark began to abide in Kiriath-jearim \uc1\u8211* twenty years. All the nation of Israel turned to the {\scaps Lord}, {\super\cf2\fs24 3}and Samuel spoke to all the nation Israel, saying, \uc1\u8220*If with all your heart you are returning to the {\scaps Lord}, then put away the foreign gods and the Astartes from among you and direct your hearts towards the {\scaps Lord} and serve him alone, so that he will deliver you out of the hand of the Philistines.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So the Israelites put away the Baals and the Astartes, and served the {\scaps Lord} only. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Then Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*Assemble all Israel at Mizpah and I will intercede for you with the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 6}So they assembled at Mizpah, and drew water and poured it out before the {\scaps Lord}, and fasted all day and confessed, \uc1\u8220*We have sinned against the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221* And Samuel judged the Israelites in Mizpah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}When the Philistines heard that the Israelites had assembled at Mizpah, the lords of the Philistines marched against Israel. When the Israelites heard of it, they were afraid of the Philistines {\super\cf2\fs24 8}and said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Don\uc1\u8217*t cease to cry to the {\scaps Lord} our God for us, so that he will save us out of the power of the Philistines.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Samuel took a sucking lamb, and offered it as a whole burnt offering to the {\scaps Lord}, and cried to the {\scaps Lord} on behalf of Israel, and the {\scaps Lord} answered him. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}While Samuel was offering the burnt offering, the Philistines drew near to fight against Israel. But the {\scaps Lord} thundered with a mighty voice on that day against the Philistines, and threw them into confusion, and they were defeated before Israel. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}The men of Israel went forth from Mizpah and pursued the Philistines and struck them until they were below Beth-car.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Then Samuel took a stone and set it between Mizpah and Jeshanah and named it Ebenezer, saying, \uc1\u8220*This is how far the {\scaps Lord} has helped us.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}So the Philistines were subdued and came no more within the border of Israel. The hand of the {\scaps Lord} was against the Philistines as long as Samuel lived. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}The cities which the Philistines had taken from Israel were restored to Israel from Ekron to Gath. Israel recovered their territory from the power of the Philistines. There was peace between Israel and the Amorites.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Samuel judged Israel all the days of his life. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}He used to go around from year to year in succession to Bethel, Gilgal, and Mizpah, and he used to judge Israel in all those places. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}But he always returned to Ramah, for there was his home, and there he judged Israel. There he built an altar to the {\scaps Lord}. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Samuel and Saul

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Development of Monarchy

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 8}When Samuel grew old he appointed his sons judges over Israel. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}The eldest was called Joel, and his second was called Abijah. They were judges in Beer-sheba. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}However his sons did not follow his ways, but turned aside after unjust gain and took bribes and perverted justice. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So all the elders of Israel assembled and came to Samuel at Ramah, {\super\cf2\fs24 5}and they said to him, \uc1\u8220*You have become old and your sons don\uc1\u8217*t follow your ways. Appoint for us a king to rule us like all the other nations.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 6}But the statement displeased Samuel, when they said, \uc1\u8220*Give us a king to judge us.\uc1\u8221* And Samuel prayed to the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The {\scaps Lord} said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Listen to the voice of the people and all that they say to you. For they have not rejected you, but they have rejected me from being king over them. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Like all the deeds which they have done to me since the day that I brought them up out of Egypt, even to this day, in that they have forsaken me and served other gods, so also are they doing to you. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Listen to what they have to say, but solemnly warn them, and show them the ways of the king who will reign over them.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Samuel told all the words of the {\scaps Lord} to the people who were asking him to appoint a king. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}He said, \uc1\u8220*This will be the way of the king who will reign over you: he will take your sons and appoint them to his chariots and cavalry. They will run before his chariots, {\super\cf2\fs24 12}and he will appoint for himself commanders of thousands and commanders of fifties, and some to plow his ground and to reap his harvest and to make his implements of war and the equipment for his chariots. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}He will take your daughters to be perfumers and to be cooks and to be bakers. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Of your fields and your vineyards and your oliveyards, he will take the best and give them to his servants. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}He will take a tenth of your grain fields and of your vineyards and give to his eunuchs and to his servants. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}He will take your male and female slaves, and the best of your cattle and your donkeys, and use them for his work. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}He will take a tenth of your flocks, and you will become his slaves. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Then you will cry out in that day against your king whom you chose for yourselves, but the {\scaps Lord} will not answer you in that day.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}But the people refused to listen to the voice of Samuel, and said, \uc1\u8220*No, we must have a king over us, {\super\cf2\fs24 20}so that we will like all other the nations, and so that our king can rule us and go out before us and fight our battles.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 21}And Samuel heard all the words of the people and repeated them to the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}And the {\scaps Lord} said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Listen to their voice and make them a king.\uc1\u8221* And Samuel said to the people of Israel, \uc1\u8220*Each of your return to your city.\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 9}Now there was a man of Benjamin, whose name was Kish the son of Abiel, the son of Zeror, the son of Becorath, the son of Aphiah, a Benjamite, a man of wealth. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}He had a son whose name was Saul, a man in the prime of life and handsome. There was no one among the Israelites more handsome than he was. He was a head taller than any of the people.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Now the donkeys of Kish, Saul\uc1\u8217*s father, had strayed. Kish said to Saul his son, \uc1\u8220*Take one of the servants with you and go out and find the donkeys.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}They passed through the hill country of Ephraim, and the land of Shalishah, but did not find them. Then they passed through the land of Shaalim, but they were not there. They passed through the land of the Benjamites but did not find them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}When they reached the land of Zuph, Saul said to his servant who was with him, \uc1\u8220*Come, let us return, or my father will stop thinking of the donkeys and become anxious for us.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 6}But the servant answered, \uc1\u8220*There is in this city a man of God, and the man is held in honor. All that he says is sure to come true. Let us go there now, and perhaps he can give us information about the mission on which we are going.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Saul said to the boy, \uc1\u8220*But, suppose we go, what should we take to the man? For the bread is gone from our sacks, and there is no present to take to the man of God. What do we have?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 8}The servant answered Saul again, \uc1\u8220*See I have with me a quarter shekel of silver, and I will give it to the man of God so that he may give us information regarding our mission.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}(Formerly in Israel, when someone went to inquire of God, they said, \uc1\u8220*Come let us go to the seer;\uc1\u8221* because what is nowadays called a prophet was previously called a seer). {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then Saul said to his servant, \uc1\u8220*Your advice is good. Come, let us go.\uc1\u8221* So they went to the city where the man of God was.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}As they were going up the ascent to the city, they met some young girls going out to draw water and said to them, \uc1\u8220*Is the seer here?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}They answered, \uc1\u8220*Yes, he is there ahead of you. Hurry, he has come today to the city because the people have a sacrifice today on the high place. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}As soon as you come to the city, you will at once find him before he goes up to the high place to eat. The people will not eat until he comes, because he is needed to bless the sacrifice before the guests eat. Now go up, and at this time you will meet him.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 14}So they went up to the city. When they came within the city gate, Samuel was just coming out toward them, to go up to the high place.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Now the {\scaps Lord} had given to Samuel, a day before Saul came, the following revelation: {\super\cf2\fs24 16}\uc1\u8220*At this time tomorrow I will send you a man out of the land of Benjamin and you must anoint him to be a prince over my people Israel. He will save my people out of the hand of the Philistines, because I have seen the suffering of my people, and their cry has reached me.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}When Samuel saw Saul, the {\scaps Lord} indicated to him, \uc1\u8220*This is the man of whom I spoke to you! He is the one who will rule over my people.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Then Saul drew near to Samuel in the gate, and said, \uc1\u8220*Tell me, please, where the seer\uc1\u8217*s house is.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}And Samuel answered Saul, \uc1\u8220*I am the seer. Go up before me to the high place, for you will eat with me today. In the morning I will let you go, and will tell you all that is in your heart. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}As for your donkeys that were lost three days ago, do not trouble yourself about them. They have been found. To whom does all that is desirable in Israel belong? Does it not belong to you, and to your ancestral house? {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Saul answered, \uc1\u8220*But I am a Benjamite, from the smallest of the tribes of Israel, and my family is the least of all the families of the tribe of Benjamin! Why do you speak like this to me?\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Samuel took Saul and his servant and brought them into the hall and made them sit at the head of the guests (who were about thirty persons). {\super\cf2\fs24 23}And he said to the cook, \uc1\u8220*Bring the portion I gave you, which I told you to put aside.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 24}The cook took up the leg and placed it before Saul. And Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*See, the meat is served! Eat! It was kept for you until the appointed time, so that you might eat with those whom I have invited.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
So Saul ate with Samuel that day. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}After they came down from the high place into the city, they spread a bed for Saul on the roof, and he lay down for the night. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}At daybreak Samuel called to Saul on the roof, \uc1\u8220*Get up, so that I can send you on your way.\uc1\u8221* So Saul arose, and he and Samuel went out into the street.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 27}As they were going down at the outskirts of the city, Samuel said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Tell your servant to go on ahead of us, but you stay here so that I can make known to you the word of God.\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 10}Then Samuel took a vial of oil, and poured it on his head, and kissed him and said, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} has anointed you to be a ruler over his people Israel. You will reign over the people of the {\scaps Lord} and save them from the power of their enemies all around. This will be the sign that the {\scaps Lord} has anointed you to be a ruler over his heritage: {\super\cf2\fs24 2}when you go from me today you will find two men at Rachel\uc1\u8217*s tomb, in the boundary of Benjamin at Zelzah. They will say to you, \uc1\u8216*The donkeys you went to seek are found, and now your father has dismissed the matter of the donkeys and is anxious for you, asking, \uc1\u8220*What should I do about my son?\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Then you will go on from there and come to the oak of Tabor. There three men going up to God to Bethel will meet you, one carrying three kids, and another carrying three loaves of bread, and another carrying a skin of wine. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}They will greet you and give you two loaves of bread which you will take from their hand. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}After that you will come to Gibeah-elohim, where the garrison of the Philistines is. When you come to the city, you will meet a band of prophets coming down from the high place with a lyre, a tambourine, a flute, and a harp before them, and they will be prophesying. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}The spirit of the {\scaps Lord} will rush upon you, and you will prophesy with them and will be turned into another man. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}When these signs come to you, you will do as the occasion offers, for God is with you. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}You must go down before me to Gilgal, and then I will come down to you, to offer burnt offerings. Wait seven days until I come to you and show you what to do.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}As Saul turned his back to go from Samuel, God gave him a change of heart, and all those signs came to pass that day. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}On his way to Gibeah, a band of prophets met him, and the spirit of God possessed him, and he prophesied among them. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}When everyone who knew him saw him in the act of prophesying with the prophets, the people said to one another, \uc1\u8220*What has come over the son of Kish? Is Saul also among the prophets?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}One of the bystanders answered, \uc1\u8220*Who is their father?\uc1\u8221* Therefore it became a proverb, \uc1\u8220*Is Saul also among the prophets?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}When he had finished prophesying, he went to the high place. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Saul\uc1\u8217*s uncle said to him and to his servant, \uc1\u8220*Where did you go?\uc1\u8221* He said, \uc1\u8220*To find the donkeys, and when we saw that they were not found, we went to Samuel.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}And Saul\uc1\u8217*s uncle said, \uc1\u8220*Tell me what Samuel said to you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}And Saul said to his uncle, \uc1\u8220*He told us that the donkeys were found.\uc1\u8221* But about the matter of the kingdom of which Samuel had spoken, he told him nothing.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Samuel called the people together to Mizpah, {\super\cf2\fs24 18}and said to the Israelites, \uc1\u8220*This is what the {\scaps Lord} the God of Israel says: I brought up Israel out of Egypt, and I delivered you out of the hand of the Egyptians, and out of the hand of all the kingdoms that were oppressing you. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}But today you rejected your God, who has been saving you from all your calamities and your distresses. You have said to him, \uc1\u8216*No! You must set a king over us.\uc1\u8217* Now therefore present yourselves before the {\scaps Lord} by your tribes and by your clans.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}So Samuel brought all the tribes of Israel near, and the tribe of Benjamin was picked by lot. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}He brought the tribe of Benjamin near by their clans, and the clan of the Matrites was picked by lot. He brought near the clan of Matri man by man and Saul the son of Kish was picked, but when they searched for him, him he could not be found. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}So they asked of the {\scaps Lord} further, \uc1\u8220*Did the man come here?\uc1\u8221* And the {\scaps Lord} answered \uc1\u8220*See, he has hid himself among the baggage.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Someone ran and brought him from there. When he stood among the people, he was taller than any of the people by a head. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Said Samuel to the people, \uc1\u8220*Have you seen this man whom the {\scaps Lord} has chosen? For there is no one like him among all the people.\uc1\u8221* All the people shouted loudly, \uc1\u8220*Long live the king!\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 25}In this way Samuel revealed to the people the manner of the kingdom, and wrote it in a book, and laid it up before the {\scaps Lord}. Then Samuel sent all the people away, each to their home. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}And Saul also went to his home at Gibeah; and with him went the warriors whose hearts God had touched. {\super\cf2\fs24 27}But there were some scoundrels who said, \uc1\u8220*How can this man save us?\uc1\u8221* They despised him, and brought him no presents. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Saul the king

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 11}About a month later Nahash the Ammonite came up and besieged Jabesh-gilead. All the men of Jabesh said to Nahash, \uc1\u8220*Make terms with us and we will serve you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}But Nahash the Ammonite said to them, \uc1\u8220*On this condition will I make terms with you: that I gouge out the right eye of each of you and by this bring disgrace on all Israel.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}The elders of Jabesh said to him, \uc1\u8220*Give us seven days respite, so that we can send messengers through all the territory of Israel. Then if there be no one to save us we will surrender to you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So the messengers came to Gibeah of Saul and recounted the facts in the hearing of the people, and all the people wept aloud.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Saul was just coming from the field, driving the oxen. He said, \uc1\u8220*What is the trouble with the people? Why are they weeping?\uc1\u8221* Then they told him the words of the men of Jabesh. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}The spirit of the {\scaps Lord} rushed upon Saul when he heard these words, and his anger was greatly aroused. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}He took a yoke of oxen, and cut them in pieces, and sent them throughout all the territory of Israel by the hand of messengers, saying, \uc1\u8220*Whoever does not come out after Saul and after Samuel, so will it be done to his oxen!\uc1\u8221* Then a terror from the {\scaps Lord} fell upon the people, and they rallied as one man.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}He mustered them in Bezek. The Israelites were three hundred thousand, and the men of Judah thirty thousand. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}They said to the messengers who came, \uc1\u8220*Say this to the men of Jabesh-gilead: Tomorrow, by the time the sun becomes hot, deliverance will have come to you.\uc1\u8221* So the messengers came and told the men of Jabesh. They rejoiced, {\super\cf2\fs24 10}and said to Nahash, \uc1\u8220*Tomorrow we will surrender to you, and you can do to us whatever you please.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}On the following day, Saul divided the people into three divisions. They came into the midst of the camp in the morning watch, and massacred the Ammonites, until the heat of the day. The survivors scattered, so that no two of them were left together.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}The people said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Who is he who said, \uc1\u8216*Saul will not reign over us?\uc1\u8217* Bring the men that we may put them to death!\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}But Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Today no one will be put to death, because today the {\scaps Lord} has brought deliverance to Israel.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Then Samuel said to the people, \uc1\u8220*Come, and let us go to Gilgal, and renew the kingdom there.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}All the people went to Gilgal. There they made Saul king before the {\scaps Lord} in Gilgal, and sacrificed peace offerings before the {\scaps Lord}, and there Saul and all the men of Israel held a great celebration. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 12}Samuel said to all Israel, \uc1\u8220*See, I have listened to you in all that you have said to me and have appointed a king over you. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}From now on, behold the king who will lead you. As for me, I am old and gray, but my sons are with you. I have led you from my youth to this day. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Here I am! Testify against me before the {\scaps Lord}, and before his annointed. Whose ox have I taken? Whose donkey have I taken? Whom have I oppressed? Whom have I defrauded? From whose hand have I taken a bribe to turn a blind eye? Testify and I will restore it to you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}They said, \uc1\u8220*You have not oppressed us, nor defrauded us, nor have you taken anything from anyone\uc1\u8217*s hand.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}So he said to them, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord} is witness against you, and his anointed is witness this day, that you have not found anything in my hand.\uc1\u8221* They said, \uc1\u8220*He is witness.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Then Samuel said to the people, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord} is witness, who appointed Moses and Aaron and who brought your ancestors up out of the land of Egypt. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Now therefore take your stand so that I may declare to you before the {\scaps Lord} all the righteous acts of the {\scaps Lord}, which he did to you and to your ancestors. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}When Jacob came to Egypt, and your ancestors cried to the {\scaps Lord}, then the {\scaps Lord} sent Moses and Aaron to bring your ancestors out of Egypt, and settled them in this place. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}But they forgot the {\scaps Lord} their God, and he sold them into the hand of Sisera, commander of the army of King Jabin of Hazor, and into the hand of the Philistines and into the hand of the king of Moab. They fought against them, {\super\cf2\fs24 10}and cried to the {\scaps Lord} and said, \uc1\u8220*We have sinned because we have forsaken the {\scaps Lord} and served the Baals and the Astartes. Deliver us out of the hand of our enemies, and we will serve you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}And the {\scaps Lord} sent Jerubbaal, and Barak, and Jephthah, and Samson, and delivered you out of the hand of your enemies surrounding you so that you lived in safety. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}But when you saw that Nahash the king of the Ammonites came against you, you said to me, \uc1\u8216*No, but a king must reign over us,\uc1\u8217* although the {\scaps Lord} your God was your king. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Now therefore see the king whom you have chosen, for the {\scaps Lord} has now set a king over you. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}If you will fear the {\scaps Lord} and serve him and listen to his voice, and not rebel against the commandment of the {\scaps Lord}, and both you and the king who reigns over you follow the {\scaps Lord} your God, then it will be well. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}But if you will not listen to the voice of the {\scaps Lord}, but rebel against the commandment of the {\scaps Lord}, then will the hand of the {\scaps Lord} be against you and your king. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Now therefore take your stand and see this great thing that the {\scaps Lord} is about to do before your eyes. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Is it not wheat harvest today? I will call upon the {\scaps Lord} to send thunder and rain. You will know and see that your wickedness is great, which you have done in the sight of the {\scaps Lord} in asking for a king.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}So Samuel called upon the {\scaps Lord}, and the {\scaps Lord} sent thunder and rain that day. All the people were greatly afraid of the {\scaps Lord} and Samuel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Then all the people said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Intercede with the {\scaps Lord} your God in behalf of your servants so that we do not die, because we have added to all our sins the crime of asking for a king.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}But Samuel said to the people, \uc1\u8220*Don\uc1\u8217*t be afraid, you have indeed done all this evil, but do not turn aside from following the {\scaps Lord}. Serve the {\scaps Lord} with all your heart, {\super\cf2\fs24 21}and do not turn aside after useless things which cannot profit or deliver, for they are useless. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}For the {\scaps Lord} because of his great name will not cast away his people, for the {\scaps Lord} has undertaken to make you his own people. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Moreover, as for me, far be it from me that I should sin against the {\scaps Lord} in ceasing to pray for you, and I will instruct you in the good and the right way. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Only fear the {\scaps Lord} and serve him in truth with all your heart, for you see the great things he has done for you. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}But if you persist in doing wrong, both you and your king will be swept away.  {\cf1 13}Saul was \uc1\u8230* years old when he began to reign, and he reigned \uc1\u8230* and two years over Israel.{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn {\super\cf2\fs24 1}  The numbers are missing from the text. }
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Saul chose three thousand men of Israel. Two thousand were with Saul in Michmash and on the mountain of Bethel and a thousand were with Jonathan in Gibeah of Benjamin. The rest of the people he sent to their homes. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Jonathan defeated the garrison of the Philistines that was in Geba, and the news reached the Philistines that the Hebrews were in revolt. But Saul had in the meantime caused the trumpet to be blown throughout all the land, {\super\cf2\fs24 4}and all Israel heard the news that Saul had defeated the garrison of the Philistines, and also that Israel had brought itself into ill odor with the Philistines. The people were called out to join Saul at Gilgal.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}The Philistines were gathered together to fight with Israel \uc1\u8211* thirty thousand chariots and six thousand horsemen and fighters as numerous as the sand on the seashore. They came up and encamped in Michmash, east of Beth-aven. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}When the Israelites saw that they were in a strait (for the fighters were hard pressed), they hid themselves in caves, in holes, in rocks, in tombs, and in pits. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Also many people went over the Jordan to the land of Gad and Gilead. But Saul was still in Gilgal, and all the people followed him trembling.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}He waited seven days for the appointed time which Samuel had set, but Samuel did not come to Gilgal, and the people scattered away from him. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}So Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Bring here to me the burnt-offering and the peace-offerings.\uc1\u8221* He offered the burnt-offering. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Just as he had finished offering the burnt-offering, Samuel came, and Saul went out to greet him. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*What have you done?\uc1\u8221* And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Because I saw that the people were scattering away from me and you did not come within the appointed time, and the Philistines were gathering together at Michmash, {\super\cf2\fs24 12}I said, \uc1\u8216*Now the Philistines will come down to me at Gilgal, and I will not have appeased the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8217* So I felt compelled to offer the burnt-offering.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Samuel said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*You have acted foolishly. If you had kept the command of the {\scaps Lord} your God, which he commanded you, then would the {\scaps Lord} have established your kingdom over Israel forever. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}But now your kingdom will not continue. The {\scaps Lord} has sought out a man after his own heart, and the {\scaps Lord} has appointed him a leader over his people, because you have not kept that which the {\scaps Lord} commanded you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Then Samuel arose and left Gilgal. The rest of the people followed Saul, going from Gilgal towards Gibeah of Benjamin.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
Saul counted the people who were with him, about six hundred men. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Saul and Jonathan his son, together with the people who were with them, were staying in Gibeah of Benjamin, while the Philistines encamped in Michmash. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Raiding parties came out of the camp of the Philistines in three divisions: one division turned in the direction of Ophrah in the land of Shual, {\super\cf2\fs24 18}and another division turned in the direction of Beth-horon, and another division turned in the direction of the hill that looks down over the valley of Zeboim toward the wilderness.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Now there was no smith found throughout all the land of Israel, for the Philistines said, \uc1\u8220*The Hebrews must not make swords or spears,\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}so all the Israelites went down to the Philistines to sharpen each his plowshare and his sickle and his ax and his mattock. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}The charge was two thirds of a shekel for ploughshares and mattocks, and one third of a shekel for sharpening the axes and setting the ox goads. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}So on the day of the battle, none of the people with Saul and Jonathan had a sword or spear; but Saul and Jonathan his son had them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 23}A garrison of the Philistines had gone out to the pass of Michmash,  {\cf1 14}and one day Jonathan the son of Saul said to the young man who bore his armor, \uc1\u8220*Come \uc1\u8211* let\uc1\u8217*s go over to the Philistines\uc1\u8217* garrison that is on the other side.\uc1\u8221* But he did not tell his father. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Saul was sitting in the outskirts of Gibeah under the pomegranate tree at Mignon, and with him were about six hundred men. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Ahijah the son of Ahitub, Ichabod\uc1\u8217*s brother, the son of Phinehas, the son of Eli, the priest of the {\scaps Lord} at Shiloh, was in charge of an ephod. The people did not know that Jonathan had gone. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Between the passes by which Jonathan sought to go over to the Philistines\uc1\u8217* garrison there was a rocky crag on the one side, and a rocky crag on the other side; and the name of the one was Bozez, and the name of the other Seneh. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}One crag rose up on the north in front of Michmash, and the other on the south in front of Geba.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Jonathan said to the young man who bore his armor, \uc1\u8220*Come, let\uc1\u8217*s go over to the garrison of these uncircumcised Philistines. Perhaps the {\scaps Lord} will act for us, for there is nothing that can prevent the {\scaps Lord} from saving by many or by few.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}His armor-bearer said to him, \uc1\u8220*Do whatever your judgement dictates. I am with you, your wish is mine.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Then Jonathan said, \uc1\u8220*We will pass over to the men and show ourselves to them. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}If they say to us, \uc1\u8216*Stand still until we can reach you,\uc1\u8217* then we will stand still in our place, and will not go up to them. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}But if they say, \uc1\u8216*Come up to us,\uc1\u8217* then we will go up; for the {\scaps Lord} has given them into our hand, and this will be the sign to us.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}When both of them showed themselves to the garrison of the Philistines, the Philistines said, \uc1\u8220*There are Hebrews coming out of the holes where they have hidden themselves.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}The men of the garrison cried out to Jonathan and his armor-bearer, \uc1\u8220*Come up to us so that we can tell you something.\uc1\u8221* Then Jonathan said to his armor-bearer, \uc1\u8220*Come up after me, for the {\scaps Lord} has given them into the hand of Israel.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}And Jonathan climbed up on his hands and feet, and his armor-bearer after him. The Philistines fell before Jonathan, and his armor-bearer kept despatching them after him. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}In the first attack Jonathan and his armor-bearer slew about twenty men in an area of about half an acre. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}There was panic in the camp, in the field, and among all the people. The garrison, and even the raiders trembled and the earth quaked so that it produced a great panic.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 16}The watchmen of Saul in Gibeah of Benjamin looked, and saw the army surging hither and thither. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Saul said to the people who were with him, \uc1\u8220*Investigate now and see who is gone from us.\uc1\u8221* When they had investigated they found that Jonathan and his armor-bearer were not there. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}And Saul said to Ahijah, \uc1\u8220*Bring the ephod here,\uc1\u8221* for at that time he had charge of the ephod before Israel. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}While Saul was speaking to the priest, the tumult in the camp of the Philistines kept on increasing. So Saul said to the priest, \uc1\u8220*Draw back your hand.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}And Saul and all the people that were with him responded to the call, and came to the battle, and every man\uc1\u8217*s sword was turned upon his fellow and there was very great confusion. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}The Hebrews who had gone over to the Philistines and joined their the camp, turned to be with the Israelites who were with Saul and Jonathan. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Likewise all the Israelites who were in hiding in the hill-country of Ephraim, when they heard that the Philistines were fleeing, pursued close after them in the battle. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}So the {\scaps Lord} saved Israel that day, and the battle passed on beyond Beth-aven.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Then Saul committed a great act of folly that day, for he laid an oath on the people, saying, \uc1\u8220*Cursed is the man who eats any food until evening and until I avenge myself on my enemies.\uc1\u8221* So none of the people tasted food. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Now there was honeycomb in that country, {\super\cf2\fs24 26}and when the people came to the honeycomb, the bees had just flown away, but no one put his hand to his mouth, for the people feared the oath. {\super\cf2\fs24 27}But Jonathan had not heard when his father charged the people. He put forth the end of the rod that was in his hand and dipped it in the honeycomb and put his hand to his mouth, and his eyes were lightened. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Then one of the fighters spoke up, \uc1\u8220*Your father charged the people saying, \uc1\u8216*Cursed be the man who eats food this day.\uc1\u8217* So the men are exhausted.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Then said Jonathan, \uc1\u8220*My father has brought disaster on the land. See how I have been refreshed, because I tasted a little of this honey. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}If only the people had eaten freely today of the spoil of their enemies which they found, how much greater would have been the slaughter of the Philistines!\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 31}But they struck at the Philistines that day from Michmash to Aijalon, and the people were very faint, {\super\cf2\fs24 32}and they rushed upon the spoil and took sheep and oxen and calves and slaughtered them on the ground, and the people ate them with the blood. {\super\cf2\fs24 33}When Saul was told that the people were sinning against the {\scaps Lord} in eating with the blood, he said to those who told him, \uc1\u8220*Treason! Roll a great stone to me.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 34}And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Go out among the people and say to them, \uc1\u8216*Let each man bring to me his ox and his sheep, and slay it here and eat; but do not sin against the {\scaps Lord} in eating the flesh together with the blood.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221* All the people brought their oxen that night and slew them there. {\super\cf2\fs24 35}So Saul built an altar to the {\scaps Lord}. That was the first altar that he built to the {\scaps Lord}.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 36}Then Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Let us go down after the Philistines by night and plunder among them until daybreak, and let us not spare a single man.\uc1\u8221* They said, \uc1\u8220*Do whatever you think best,\uc1\u8221* but the priest said, \uc1\u8220*Let us first consut God.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 37}So Saul asked of God, \uc1\u8220*Should I go down after the Philistines? Will you deliver them into the hand of Israel?\uc1\u8221* But there was no answer that day. {\super\cf2\fs24 38}And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Come here, all you chiefs of the people and know and see in whom is this guilt today. {\super\cf2\fs24 39}For as the {\scaps Lord} lives, who delivered Israel, even if it be in Jonathan my son, that man will surely die.\uc1\u8221* But no one of all the people answered him. {\super\cf2\fs24 40}Then he said to all Israel, \uc1\u8220*You will on one side, and I and Jonathan my son will be on the other side.\uc1\u8221* The people said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Do what seems good to you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 41}Therefore Saul asked the {\scaps Lord}, God of Israel, \uc1\u8220*Why have you not answered your servant this day? If the guilt is in me or in Jonathan my son, the {\scaps Lord}, God of Israel, give Urim, but if the guilt is in your people Israel, give Thummim.\uc1\u8221* And the lot indicated Jonathan and Saul, and the people were cleared. {\super\cf2\fs24 42}And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Cast the lot between me and Jonathan my son. He whom the {\scaps Lord} indicates, must die.\uc1\u8221* The people said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*It must not be so!\uc1\u8221* But Saul overruled the people and they cast the lot between him and Jonathan his son. And Jonathan was indicated.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 43}Then Saul said to Jonathan, \uc1\u8220*Tell me what you have done.\uc1\u8221* And Jonathan told him, saying, \uc1\u8220*I did indeed taste a little honey with the end of the staff that was in my hand, and here I am! I am ready to die.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 44}And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*May God do to me whatever he pleases, you must surely die, Jonathan!\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 45}But the people said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Should Jonathan die who has wrought this great victory in Israel? Far from it! As the {\scaps Lord} lives, not one hair of his head will fall to the ground, for he has worked with God this day.\uc1\u8221* So the people redeemed Jonathan, so that he did not die. {\super\cf2\fs24 46}Then Saul broke off from pursuing the Philistines and the Philistines went to their own country.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 47}When Saul had taken the kingdom over Israel, he fought against all his enemies on every side: against Moab and the Ammonites and Edom and the kings of Zobah, and the Philistines. Wherever he turned he was victorious. {\super\cf2\fs24 48}He did mighty deeds and struck the Amalekites and delivered Israel out of the hands of its plunderers.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 49}Now the sons of Saul were: Jonathan, Ishvi, and Malchishua. The names of his two daughters were: the eldest, Merab, the youngest, Michal. {\super\cf2\fs24 50}The name of Saul\uc1\u8217*s wife was Ahinoam the daughter of Ahimaaz. The name of the commander of his army was Abner the son Saul\uc1\u8217*s uncle Ner. {\super\cf2\fs24 51}Kish the father of Saul and Ner the father of Abner were sons of Abiel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 52}The war against the Philistines was severe all the days of Saul. Whenever Saul saw any valiant or efficient man, he would take him into his service. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 15}Samuel said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} sent me to anoint you to be king over his people Israel. Now listen to the words of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}This says the {\scaps Lord} of armies: \uc1\u8216*I have determined to punish the Amalekites for wha they did to Israel, in opposing them as they came up out of Egypt. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Now go and attack Amalek and utterly destroy all that they have. Spare no one but slay both man and woman, child and infant, ox and sheep, camel and donkey.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So Saul summoned the people and mustered them in Telaim, two hundred thousand foot soldiers and ten thousand from Judah. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}When Saul came to the city of Amalek, he lay in wait in the valley. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Saul said to the Kenites, \uc1\u8220*Go away, withdraw from among the Amalekites, or I will destroy you with them, for you showed kindness to all the Israelites when they came up from Egypt.\uc1\u8221* So the Kenites departed from among the Amalekites. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}And Saul struck the Amalekites from Havilah as far as Shur, which is east of Egypt. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}He took Agag the king of Amalek alive and completely destroyed all the people with the sword. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}But Saul and his army spared Agag and the best of the sheep, the oxen, the fat beasts, the lambs, and all that was good, and would not completely destroy them. But everything that was worthless and despised they completely destroyed.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then the word of the {\scaps Lord} came to Samuel saying, {\super\cf2\fs24 11}\uc1\u8220*I repent of making Saul king, because he has turned from following me and has not carried out my commands.\uc1\u8221* And Samuel was angry and cried to the {\scaps Lord} all night. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Early in the morning Samuel rose to meet Saul. Then Samuel was told, \uc1\u8220*Saul came to Carmel and has just set up a monument to himself and has turned and passed on and gone down to Gilgal.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}When Samuel came to Saul, Saul said to him, \uc1\u8220*Blessed be you of the {\scaps Lord}! I have fulfilled the command of the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 14}And Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*What then is this bleating of the sheep in my ears and the lowing of the cattle which I hear?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*They have brought them from the Amalekites, for the people spared the best off the sheep and of the oxen to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord} your God, and the rest we have completely destroyed.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Then Samuel said to \uc1\u8220*Saul, Stop! and let me tell you what the {\scaps Lord} has said to me this night.\uc1\u8221* He said to him, \uc1\u8220*Speak.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*Though you are little in your own sight, are you not the head of the tribes of Israel? And the {\scaps Lord} anointed you king over Israel, {\super\cf2\fs24 18}and the {\scaps Lord} sent you on an expedition and said, \uc1\u8216*Go, and completely destroy the sinners of Amalek and fight against them until they are consumed.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Why then did you not obey the voice of the {\scaps Lord} and why did you swoop upon the spoil and displease the {\scaps Lord}?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}And Saul said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*I have obeyed the voice of the {\scaps Lord} and have gone on the expedition which the {\scaps Lord} sent me on and have brought back Agag the king of the Amalekites and have completely destroyed the Amalekites. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}But the people took of the spoil, sheep and oxen, the best of the things which were placed under the ban, to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord} your God in Gilgal.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 22}And Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*Does the {\scaps Lord} delight in burnt-offerings and sacrifices as in obedience to the voice of the {\scaps Lord}? Behold to obey is better than sacrifice, and to listen than the fat of rams. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}For rebellion is as bad as the sin of divination, and obstinacy as idolatry. Because you have rejected the word of the {\scaps Lord}, he has rejected you from being king.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 24}And Saul said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*I have sinned, for I have transgressed the command of the {\scaps Lord} and your words because I feared the people and listened to their voice. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Now therefore pardon for my sin and turn back with me, that I may worship the {\scaps Lord}.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 26}But Samuel said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*I will not turn back with you, for you have rejected the word of the {\scaps Lord} and the {\scaps Lord} has rejected you from being king over Israel.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 27}As Samuel turned to go away, Saul seized the skirt of his robe, but it tore. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Then Samuel said to him, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord} has today torn the kingdom of Israel from you and has given it to your neighbor who is better than you. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Moreover the Glory of Israel will not lie nor repent, for he is not a mortal that he should change his mind.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 30}Then Saul said, \uc1\u8220*I have sinned, yet honor me now at least before the elders of my people and before Israel, and turn back with me, so that I may worship the {\scaps Lord} your God.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 31}So Samuel turned back and followed Saul, while Saul worshipped the {\scaps Lord}.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 32}Then Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*Bring here to me Agag the king of the Amalekites.\uc1\u8221* And Agag came to him trembling and said, \uc1\u8220*Surely death is bitter.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 33}Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*As your sword has bereaved women, so will your mother be the most bereaved of women.\uc1\u8221* Then Samuel hewed Agag in pieces before the {\scaps Lord} in Gilgal.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 34}Then Samuel went to Ramah, but Saul went up to his house to Gibeah of Saul. {\super\cf2\fs24 35}And Samuel did not see Saul again until the day of his death, for Samuel grieved over Saul. Now the {\scaps Lord} repented that he had made Saul king over Israel. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Saul, Jonathan, and David

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 David at the court of Saul

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 16}The {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*How long will you grieve over Saul, when I have rejected him from being king over Israel? Fill your horn with oil and go. I will send you to Jesse the Bethlehemite, for I have chosen for myself a king among his sons.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}And Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*How can I go, since Saul will hear of it and kill me?\uc1\u8221* But the {\scaps Lord} said, \uc1\u8220*Take a calf with you and say you have come to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Invite Jesse to the sacrifice, and I will show you what to do, and anoint the man whom I name.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So Samuel did that which the {\scaps Lord} had commanded. When he came to Bethlehem, the elders of the city came trembling to meet him and said, \uc1\u8220*Do you come in peace?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}He said \uc1\u8220*Yes, I have come to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord}. Purify yourselves and rejoiced with me in the sacrifice.\uc1\u8221* He purified Jesse and his sons and invited them to the sacrifice.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}When they came and he saw Eliab, he said, \uc1\u8220*Surely the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s annointed is now in presence.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}But the {\scaps Lord} said to Samuel, \uc1\u8220*Pay no attention to his appearance or to the height of his stature, because I have rejected him. The {\scaps Lord} does not see as humans see, for they look on the outward appearance, but the {\scaps Lord} looks at the heart.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Then Jesse called Abinadab, and brought him before Samuel. But he said, \uc1\u8220*Neither has the {\scaps Lord} chosen this one.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Then Jesse brought forward Shammah. But he said, Neither hath the {\scaps Lord} chosen this one. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then Jesse brought his seven sons before Samuel. But Samuel said to Jesse, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord} has not chosen these.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}And Samuel said to Jesse, \uc1\u8220*Are these all your sons?\uc1\u8221* He said, \uc1\u8220*There is still the youngest, but he is a shepherd with the flock.\uc1\u8221* So Samuel said to Jesse, \uc1\u8220*Send and bring him, for we will not sit down until he is brought here.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}So he sent and brought him in. Now he was handsome, a youth with beautiful eyes and ruddy cheeks. And the {\scaps Lord} said, \uc1\u8220*Get up, anoint him, for this is the man.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Then Samuel took the horn of oil and anointed him in the midst of his brothers. The spirit of the {\scaps Lord} came with power upon David from that day forward. And Samuel arose and went to Ramah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Now the spirit of the {\scaps Lord} had departed from Saul and an evil spirit from the {\scaps Lord} tormented him. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}And Saul\uc1\u8217*s servants said to him, \uc1\u8220*See now, an evil spirit from God is tormenting you. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Command your servants who are before and they will seek for our lord a man skilful in playing the lyre. Then whenever the evil spirit comes upon you he will play with his hand, and you will be better.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}So Saul said to his servants, \uc1\u8220*Provide me now someone who plays well, and bring him to me.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}One of the young men answered, \uc1\u8220*I have seen a son of Jesse the Bethlehemite who is skilful in playing and a valiant man, a good fighter, judicious in speech, a man of good appearance, and the {\scaps Lord} is with him.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}So Saul sent messengers to Jesse and said, \uc1\u8220*Send me David your son, who is with the flock.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}And Jesse took ten loaves of bread, and a skin of wine, and a kid, and sent them to Saul with David his son. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}So David came to Saul and entered his service. Saul loved him so much that he became one of his armor-bearers, {\super\cf2\fs24 22}and sent a message to Jesse, saying, \uc1\u8220*Let David enter my service, for he has found favor in my sight.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Whenever the evil spirit from God came upon Saul, David would take the lyre and play with his hand and Saul would breathe freely and would feel better and the evil spirit would depart from him. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 17}Now the Philistines mustered together their forces for war. They were gathered together at Socoh, which belongs to Judah, and encamped between Socoh and Azekah, in Ephes-dammim. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Saul and the men of Israel were gathered together and encamped in the valley of Elah, and they drew up in battle-array against the Philistines. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}The Philistines were standing on the mountain on the one side, and the Israelites were standing on the mountain on the other side, and the valley was between them. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}A champion came out from the camp of the Philistines. His name was Goliath of Gath and he was over nine feet in height. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}He had a helmet of bronze on his head, and he was clad with a bronze breastplate of scales, the weight of which was about two hundred pounds. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}He had greaves of bronze on his legs and a javelin of bronze slung between his shoulders. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The shaft of his spear was like a weaver\uc1\u8217*s beam, and the head of his iron spear weighed twenty-four pounds. His shield-bearer went before him. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}He stood and cried out to the ranks of Israel, \uc1\u8220*Why have you come out to draw up the line of battle? Am not I a Philistine and you Saul\uc1\u8217*s servants? Choose a man for yourselves and let him come down to me. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}If he is able to fight with me and kill me, then we will be your servants. But if I prevail against him and kill him, then you will be our servants and serve us.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}The Philistine said, \uc1\u8220*I have insulted the ranks of Israel today! Give me a man that we may fight together.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}When Saul and all Israel heard these words of the Philistine, they were terrified and greatly afraid.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Now David was the son of an Ephrathite of Bethlehem in Judah, whose name was Jesse. Jesse had eight sons. The man was old in the days of Saul, advanced in years among men. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}The three eldest sons of Jesse had gone after Saul to the war. Their names were Eliab, the eldest, his second Abinadab, and the third Shammah. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}David was the youngest. The three eldest had followed Saul, {\super\cf2\fs24 15}while David went to and fro from Saul to feed his father\uc1\u8217*s sheep at Bethlehem.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 16}The Philistine drew near morning and evening and took his stand for forty days. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}One day Jesse said to David his son, \uc1\u8220*Take now for your brothers a bushel of this parched grain and these ten loaves and carry them quickly to the camp to your brothers. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}But bring these ten cheeses to the commander of their thousand and look after your brothers\uc1\u8217* welfare and bring back some token of assurance from them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}They are with Saul and all the men of Israel in the valley of Elah fighting with the Philistines.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}So David rose up early in the morning and left the flock with a keeper and went, as Jesse had commanded him. He came to the encampments just as the army was going forth to the battle-array, shouting the war cry. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Israel and the Philistines drew up the line of battle, army confronting army. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}David left his vessels in the charge of the keeper of the baggage and ran to the line of battle and came and asked for the welfare of his brothers. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Just as he was talking with them, the champion, the Philistine of Gath, Goliath by name, came up out of the ranks of the Philistines and spoke the same words as before, and David heard them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}All the men of Israel, when they saw the man, fled from him and were greatly afraid. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}\uc1\u8220*Have you seen this man who has come up?\uc1\u8221* they said, \uc1\u8220*Surely he has come up to insult Israel. Whoever kills him, the king will greatly enrich and will give him his daughter and will make his father\uc1\u8217*s house free in Israel.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Then David spoke to the men who stood by him, \uc1\u8220*What should be done for the man who strikes that Philistine and takes away the reproach from Israel? For who is this uncircumcised Philistine, that he has dared to insult the armies of the living God?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 27}The people answered him in the words just given, \uc1\u8220*This is what will be done to the man who kills him.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Eliab his eldest brother heard when he spoke to the men. Eliab\uc1\u8217*s anger was kindled against David, and he said, \uc1\u8220*Why have you come down? With whom have you left those few sheep in the wilderness? I know you well and the wickedness of your heart. You have come down to see the battle.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 29}David said, \uc1\u8220*What have I done now? It was only a question.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 30}Turning away from him to another, he spoke as before, and the people answered him again as at the first time.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 31}When the words were heard which David spoke, they reported them to Saul. They took him and brought him before Saul. {\super\cf2\fs24 32}David said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Let not my lord\uc1\u8217*s courage fail him. Your servant will go and fight with this Philistine.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 33}Saul answered, \uc1\u8220*You are not able to go against this Philistine to fight with him. You are only a youth and he has been a warrior from his youth.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 34}But David said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Your servant was a shepherd with his father\uc1\u8217*s flock, and when a lion or a bear would come and take a lamb out of the flock, {\super\cf2\fs24 35}I would go out after him and kill him and rescue the lamb from his mouth. If he rose up against me, I would seize him by his jaw and slay him with a blow. {\super\cf2\fs24 36}Your servant has killed both lion and bear. Now this uncircumcised Philistine will be like one of them, since he has insulted the armies of the living God. {\super\cf2\fs24 37}The {\scaps Lord} who delivered me from the paw of the lion, and from the paw of the bear, will deliver me from the hand of this Philistine.\uc1\u8221* So Saul said to David, \uc1\u8220*Go, and may the {\scaps Lord} be with you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 38}Saul clothed David with his armor, and put a helmet of bronze on his head and clad him with a coat of mail. {\super\cf2\fs24 39}David girded his sword over his coat and made a vain attempt to go, for he had not tried them. Then David said to Saul, I cannot go with these because I am not used to them. And he took them off. {\super\cf2\fs24 40}He took his staff in his hand, and chose five smooth stones out of the brook and put them in his bag, and took his sling in his hand, and he drew near to the Philistine.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 41}The Philistine kept coming nearer to David, and the man who was bearing the shield went before him. {\super\cf2\fs24 42}When the Philistine looked and saw David, he had nothing but disdain for him, because he was only a youth with ruddy cheeks, a young man of attractive appearance. {\super\cf2\fs24 43}The Philistine said to David, \uc1\u8220*Am I a dog that you come to me with a stick?\uc1\u8221* The Philistine cursed David by his gods, {\super\cf2\fs24 44}and said, \uc1\u8220*Come to me so that I may give your flesh to the birds of the heavens and to the beasts of the field.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 45}Then David answered the Philistine, \uc1\u8220*You come to me with a sword and a spear and a javelin, but I come to you in the name of the {\scaps Lord} of armies, and the God of the ranks of Israel whom you have insulted. {\super\cf2\fs24 46}Today the {\scaps Lord} will deliver you into my hands, that I may strike you and cut off your head. I will this day give the dead of the army of the Philistines to the birds of the heavens and to the wild beasts of the earth, so that all the world may know that there is a God in Israel, {\super\cf2\fs24 47}so that all this assembly may know that not with the sword and spear does the {\scaps Lord} save, for the battle is the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s and he will give you into our hand.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 48}When the Philistine arose and came and drew near to meet David, David quickly ran toward the line of battle to meet the Philistine. {\super\cf2\fs24 49}David put his hand in his bag and took from it a stone and slung it and struck the Philistine on his forehead. The stone sank into his forehead, so that he fell on his face to the earth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 50}So David prevailed over the Philistine with a sling and with a stone and struck down the Philistine, killing him, although there was no sword in David\uc1\u8217*s hand. {\super\cf2\fs24 51}Then David ran and stood over the Philistine, and took his sword, drawing it out of its sheath, and slew him, and cut off his head with it.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
When the Philistines saw that their champion was dead, they fled. {\super\cf2\fs24 52}The men of Israel and Judah arose and raised the battle cry and pursued the Philistines to the entrance to Gath and to the gates of Ekron, so that the wounded of the Philistines fell down on the way from Shaaraim, as far as Gath and Ekron. {\super\cf2\fs24 53}When the Israelites returned from pursuing the Philistines, they plundered their camp, {\super\cf2\fs24 54}but David took the head of the Philistine and brought it to Jerusalem; and he put his armor in his tent.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 55}When Saul saw David going out against the Philistine, he said to Abner, the commander of the army, \uc1\u8220*Abner, whose son is this lad?\uc1\u8221* And Abner said, \uc1\u8220*As you live, O king, I cannot tell.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 56}The king said, \uc1\u8220*Inquire whose son the young man is.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 57}When David returned from killing the Philistine, Abner took him, and brought him before Saul with the Philistine\uc1\u8217*s head in his hand. {\super\cf2\fs24 58}Saul said to him, \uc1\u8220*Whose son are you, my lad?\uc1\u8221* And David answered, \uc1\u8220*I am the son of your servant Jesse the Bethlehemite.\uc1\u8221*  {\cf1 18}Now when David had finished speaking with Saul, the lives of Jonathan and David became bound together, and Jonathon loved him as his own life, {\super\cf2\fs24 2}and so Saul took David that day and would not let him return to his father\uc1\u8217*s house. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Jonathan made a covenant with David, because he loved him as his own life. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}He stripped himself of the cloak which he had on and gave it to David and his military coat, even to his sword and to his bow and to his girdle. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}And David went out. On every task which Saul sent him, he acted wisely and with success, so that Saul appointed him over the warriors. He was beloved alike by all the people and by the servants of Saul.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}At the return home of the army and David\uc1\u8217*s return from slaying the Philistine, the women came out dancing from all the cities of Israel to meet King Saul with tambourines, with cries of rejoicing, and with cymbals. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The women sang to each other as they danced, \uc1\u8220*Saul has slain his thousands, but David his ten thousands.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 8}It made Saul very angry, and this saying displeased him. He said, \uc1\u8220*They ascribed to David ten thousands, while to me they ascribed but thousands, and what more can he have but the kingdom?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}And Saul kept his eye on David from that day forward.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}The next day an evil spirit from God came powerfully on Saul, and he prophesied within his house. David played the lyre to him, as he did day by day. Saul had his spear in his hand, {\super\cf2\fs24 11}and cast it, thinking, \uc1\u8220*I will pin David to the wall.\uc1\u8221* But twice David dodged it.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Saul was afraid of David, because the {\scaps Lord} was with him and had departed from Saul. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}So Saul removed him from his presence, and made him a commander over a thousand. David went out and came in at the head of his men, {\super\cf2\fs24 14}and he acted wisely and prospered in all his ways, for the {\scaps Lord} was with him. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}When Saul saw that David acted wisely and prospered, he stood in dread of him. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}But all Israel and Judah loved David, for he went out and came in at the head of the army.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Then Saul said to David, \uc1\u8220*See my oldest daughter, Merab. I will give her to you as wife, only be a valiant champion and fight the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s battles.\uc1\u8221* For Saul said to himself, \uc1\u8220*I must not raise my hand against him, but let the hand of the Philistines deal with him.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}And David replied to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Who am I, and what is my father\uc1\u8217*s clan in Israel, that I should be the king\uc1\u8217*s son-in-law?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}But when the time came that Merab, Saul\uc1\u8217*s daughter, should have been given to David, she was instead given as wife to Adriel the Meholathite.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Michal, Saul\uc1\u8217*s daughter, fell in love with David. When they told Saul, he was pleased. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}He thought, \uc1\u8220*I will give her to him, so that she becomes a snare to him and that the hand of the Philistines may be against him.\uc1\u8221* Therefore Saul said to David a second time, \uc1\u8220*You will this day be my son-in-law.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Saul commanded his servants, \uc1\u8220*Communicate with David secretly and tell him that the king is pleased with him and all the servants love him, therefore become the king\uc1\u8217*s son-in-law.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 23}And Saul\uc1\u8217*s servants spoke these words in the ears of David. And David said, \uc1\u8220*Is it an easy thing in your opinion to become the king\uc1\u8217*s son-in-law, when I am a poor man and of no reputation?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 24}The servants of Saul reported back what David had said. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}And Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Tell David: The king desires no bride-price, but a hundred foreskins of the Philistines, in order to take vengeance on the king\uc1\u8217*s enemies.\uc1\u8221* Saul thought to make David fall by the hand of the Philistines. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}When his servants told David these words, David was well pleased with the prospect of being the king\uc1\u8217*s son-in-law. Before the appointed time, {\super\cf2\fs24 27}he arose and went together with his men and slew a hundred Philistines. He brought their foreskins and gave them in full to the king, in order to become the king\uc1\u8217*s son-in-law. So Saul gave him Michal his daughter as wife. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}When Saul saw and knew that the {\scaps Lord} was with David and his daughter Michal loved him, {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Saul feared David still more, and from that time was David\uc1\u8217*s enemy.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 30}The Philistine commanders continued to come out to battle, and as often as they came out, David acted more wisely and with greater success than all the servants of Saul, so that his name was held in high repute. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 David flees Saul

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 19}Saul commanded Jonathan his son and all his servants to put David to death. But Jonathan, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, was very fond of David, {\super\cf2\fs24 2}and told David, \uc1\u8220*Saul my father is seeking to put you to death. Now, I beg you, take care in the morning and stay in concealment and hide yourself. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}I will go out and stand beside my father in the field where you are, and I will speak to my father about you, and whatever I discover I will tell you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Jonathan spoke well of David to Saul his father, and said to him, \uc1\u8220*Let not the king sin against his servant David, because he has not sinned against you and because his conduct toward you has been exceedingly good. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}He took his life in his hand and killed the Philistine, and the {\scaps Lord} wrought a great deliverance for Israel. You saw it and rejoiced. Why then will you sin against innocent blood, in slaying David without a cause?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 6}And Saul listened to the voice of Jonathan and gave an oath, \uc1\u8220*As the {\scaps Lord} lives, David will not be put to death.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}And Jonathan called David, and told him all these words. And Jonathan brought David to Saul, so that he was again in his presence as before.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}But when there was war again, David went out and fought against the Philistines, and slew great numbers of them, so that they fled before him. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Then an evil spirit from the {\scaps Lord} came upon Saul, while he was sitting in his house with his spear in his hand, and David was playing on the lyre. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}And Saul sought to pin David to the wall with the spear, but he slipped away out of Saul\uc1\u8217*s presence, so that Saul hurled the spear into the wall, and David fled and escaped.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}That night Saul sent messengers to David\uc1\u8217*s house to watch him, so as to kill him in the morning. But Michal, David\uc1\u8217*s wife, told him, \uc1\u8220*If you do not save your life tonight, tomorrow you will be slain.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Michal let David down through the window; he fled away and escaped. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Michal took the household god and laid it in the bed, and put a cloth of goat\uc1\u8217*s hair for its head and covered it with the garment. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}When Saul sent messengers to take David, she said, \uc1\u8220*He is sick.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Then Saul sent the messengers to see David, saying, \uc1\u8220*Bring him up to me in the bed, that I may put him to death.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}When the messengers came in, there the household god was in the bed, with the cloth of goat\uc1\u8217*s hair for its pillow. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}And Saul said to Michal, \uc1\u8220*Why have you deceived me like this, and let my enemy go, so that he has escaped?\uc1\u8221* And Michal answered Saul, \uc1\u8220*He said to me: Let me go, why should I kill you?\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Now David fled and escaped and came to Samuel to Ramah and told him all that Saul had done to him. He and Samuel went and stayed in Naioth. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}When Saul was told thqt David was there at Naioth in Ramah, {\super\cf2\fs24 20}he sent messengers to take David. But when they saw the company of the prophets prophesying with Samuel standing as head over them, the spirit of God came upon the messengers of Saul, so that they also prophesied. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}When it was told Saul, he sent other messengers, and they also prophesied. And Saul sent messengers again the third time, and they also prophesied. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Then Saul himself went to Ramah. When he came to the great cistern in Secu, he asked, \uc1\u8220*Where are Samuel and David?\uc1\u8221* Someone answered, \uc1\u8220*They are at Naioth in Ramah.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 23}But on his journey to Naioth in Ramah, the spirit of God also came upon him, and he went along prophesying, until he came to Naioth in Ramah. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}He too stripped off his clothes and prophesied before Samuel, and lay naked all that day and all that night. Therefore they say, \uc1\u8220*Is Saul also among the prophets?\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 20}David fled from Naioth in Ramah. He came to Jonathan and said, \uc1\u8220*What have I done? What is my guilt? What is my sin against your father, that he is seeking my life?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}He replied to him, \uc1\u8220*Far from it! You will not die. See, my father does nothing great or small, but that he discloses it to than me; and why should my father hide this from me? It can\uc1\u8217*t be true!\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}David answered, \uc1\u8220*Your father well knows that I have found favor in your eyes, and he is saying to himself, \uc1\u8216*Let not Jonathan know this or he will be pained.\uc1\u8217* Nevertheless as surely as the {\scaps Lord} lives, and as you live, there is but a step between me and death.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Then Jonathan said to David, \uc1\u8220*What do you want me to do for you?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}And David answered Jonathan, \uc1\u8220*Tomorrow is the new moon and I should not fail to sit at the table with the king. Therefore let me go and I will hide myself in the field until evening. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}If your father misses me, then say, \uc1\u8216*David urgently asked leave of me to run to Bethlehem his city; for the yearly sacrifice is there for all the family.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}If he says \uc1\u8216*Good,\uc1\u8217* then it is well with your servant, but if it arouses his anger, then know that he intends evil on me. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Now deal kindly with your servant, for you have brought your servant into a sacred covenant with you. If there is guilt in me, slay me yourself, for why should you bring me to your father?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}And Jonathan said, \uc1\u8220*No! For if I should learn that my father had determined that evil should come upon you, I would tell you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then David said to Jonathan, \uc1\u8220*Who will tell me, if your father answers you harshly?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}And Jonathan replied to David, \uc1\u8220*Come, and let us go out into the field.\uc1\u8221* So the two of them went out into the field. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}And Jonathan said to David, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord}, the God of Israel, be witness that I will sound my father about this time tomorrow or the next day, and if is well disposed toward David, then I will send and disclose it to you. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}May God do to Jonathan whatever he will, should my father be disposed to do you evil, and I disclose it not to you and send you away that you may go in peace. May the {\scaps Lord} be with you, as he has been with my father. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}If I am yet alive, show me the kindness of the {\scaps Lord}! But if I should die, {\super\cf2\fs24 15}continue your kindness to my household forever, even if the {\scaps Lord} has cut off every one of David\uc1\u8217*s enemies from the face of the earth.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}So Jonathan made a covenant with the house of David, saying, \uc1\u8220*May the {\scaps Lord} seek out the enemies of David.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Jonathan took an oath again with David, because of his love to him. With all his heart he loved him. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Then Jonathan said to him, \uc1\u8220*Tomorrow is the new moon and you will be missed, because your seat will be empty. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}On the third day you will be greatly missed. Then you should go to the place where you hid yourself the other time, and sit down there beside the heap of stones. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}I will shoot three arrows on one side of it, as though I shot at a mark. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Then I will send the boy, saying, \uc1\u8216*Go, find the arrows.\uc1\u8217* If I say to the boy, \uc1\u8216*See, the arrows are on this side of you, pick them up!\uc1\u8217* \uc1\u8211* then come; for it is safe for you, and, as the {\scaps Lord} lives, there is no danger. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}But if I say to the boy, \uc1\u8216*See, the arrows are beyond you,\uc1\u8217*, go, for then the {\scaps Lord} sends you away. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}As to the word which you and I have spoken, behold, the {\scaps Lord} is witness between you and me forever.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}So David hid himself in the field; and when the new moon came, the king sat down at the table to eat. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}The king sat upon his seat as usual, on the seat by the wall, with Jonathan opposite, and Abner sat by Saul\uc1\u8217*s side; but David\uc1\u8217*s place was empty. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Nevertheless Saul did not say anything that day, for he thought, \uc1\u8216*It is an accident, he is not ceremonially clean, for he has not been cleansed.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 27}But when on the day following the new moon, David\uc1\u8217*s place was empty, Saul said to Jonathan his son, \uc1\u8220*Why has not the son of Jesse come to the meal, either yesterday or today?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 28}And Jonathan answered Saul, \uc1\u8220*David urgently asked leave of me to go to Bethlehem, {\super\cf2\fs24 29}for he said, \uc1\u8216*Let me go, since our family has a sacrifice in the city; and my brothers have commanded me. Now if I have found favor in your sight, let me slip away and see my brothers.\uc1\u8217* Hence he has not come to the king\uc1\u8217*s table.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 30} Then Saul\uc1\u8217*s anger was kindled against Jonathan, and he said to him, \uc1\u8220*Son of a depraved woman! Don\uc1\u8217*t I know that you are associated with the son of Jesse to your own shame and to the shame of your mother\uc1\u8217*s nakedness? {\super\cf2\fs24 31}For as long as the son of Jesse lives on the earth, neither you nor your kingdom will be established. Now send and bring him to me, for he is doomed to die.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 32}Then Jonathan answered Saul his father \uc1\u8220*Why should he be put to death? What has he done?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 33}But Saul lifted up his spear at him to strike him. So Jonathan knew that his father had determined to put David to death. {\super\cf2\fs24 34}Jonathan rose from the table in hot anger and ate no food the second day of the month, for he was grieved for David, because his father reviled him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 35}In the morning Jonathan went out into the field at the time appointed with David, and a little boy with him. {\super\cf2\fs24 36}He said to his boy, \uc1\u8220*Run, find and the arrows which I shoot.\uc1\u8221* As the boy ran, he shot an arrow beyond him. {\super\cf2\fs24 37}When the boy came to the place where the arrow which Jonathan had shot lay, Jonathan cried after the boy, and said, \uc1\u8220*Isn\uc1\u8217*t the arrow beyond you?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 38}Jonathan cried after the boy, \uc1\u8220*Hurry, quick, do not stop!\uc1\u8221* So Jonathan\uc1\u8217*s boy gathered up the arrows, and brought them to his master. {\super\cf2\fs24 39}But the boy had no knowledge of anything. Only Jonathan and David understood what this meant. {\super\cf2\fs24 40}Jonathan gave his weapons to his boy, and said to him, \uc1\u8220*Go, carry them to the city.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 41}As soon as the lad had gone, David rose from beside the stone heap, and fell on his face to the ground and prostrated himself three times, and they kissed each other and wept at length with each other. {\super\cf2\fs24 42}Then Jonathan said to David, \uc1\u8220*Go in peace! As to what we two have sworn in the name of the {\scaps Lord} \uc1\u8211* the {\scaps Lord} will be between me and you and between my descendants and your descendants forever.\uc1\u8221* Then David rose and departed and Jonathan went into the city. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 21}David came to Nob, to Ahimelech the priest. Ahimelech came trembling to meet David and said to him, \uc1\u8220*Why are you alone and no one with you?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}David answered Ahimelech the priest, \uc1\u8220*The king has entrusted me with a matter and has said to me, \uc1\u8216*Let no one know anything about the matter upon which I am sending you and which I have commanded you.\uc1\u8217* I have directed the young men to meet me at a certain place. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Now if you have five loaves of bread at hand, or whatever can be found, give it to me.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}The priest answered David, \uc1\u8220*There is no ordinary bread at hand. There is holy bread, but only if the young men have kept themselves from women.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}David answered the priest, \uc1\u8220*Women have been kept from us, as always when I set out on an expedition. The weapons of the young men were consecrated even on an ordinary journey; how much more then today will their weapons be holy!\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 6}So the priest gave him holy bread, for there was no bread there but the bread of the Presense, that was taken from before the {\scaps Lord} in order to put hot bread there the day it was taken away.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}(Now one of the servants of Saul was there that day, detained before the {\scaps Lord}. His name was Doeg, an Edomite, the chief of Saul\uc1\u8217*s herdsmen.) {\super\cf2\fs24 8}David said to Ahimelech, \uc1\u8220*Have you not here at hand a spear or sword? For I brought neither my sword nor my weapons with me, because the king\uc1\u8217*s matter required haste.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}The priest said, \uc1\u8220*The sword of Goliath the Philistine, whom you slew in the valley of Elah, is here, wrapped in a garment behind the ephod. If you wish to take that, take it, for there is no other except that here.\uc1\u8221* And David said, \uc1\u8220*There is none like that, give it to me.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then David rose and fled that day from before Saul, and went to Achish the king of Gath. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}The servants of Achish said to him, \uc1\u8220*Isn\uc1\u8217*t this David the king of the land? Was it not of him that they used to sing to each other in the dances, saying,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
Saul has slain his thousands,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
But David his ten thousands?\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}David took these words to his heart and was greatly afraid of Achish the king of Gath. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}He pretended to be insane before them, and raved in their hands and drummed on the doors and let his spittle run down his beard. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Achish said to his servants, \uc1\u8220*You see plainly that the man is mad; why do you bring him to me? {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Do I lack madmen that you have brought this fellow to act the madman in my presence? Should this one come into my house?\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 22}So David left there and escaped to the cave of Adullam. When his brothers and all his father\uc1\u8217*s clan heard of it, they went down there to him. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Everyone who was in distress, and everyone who was in debt, and everyone who was embittered gathered about him, and he became their leader. There were about four hundred men with him. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}David went from there to Mizpeh in Moab. He said to the king of Moab, \uc1\u8220*Let my father and my mother shelter with you, until I know what God will do for me.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}He left them in the presences of the king of Moab, and they stayed with him all the while that David was in the stronghold. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Then the prophet Gad said to David, \uc1\u8220*Do not remain in the stronghold. Depart and go to the land of Judah.\uc1\u8221* So David left and went into the forest of Hereth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}When Saul heard that David and the men with him were discovered, he was sitting in Gibeah, under the tamarisk tree on the high place, with his spear in his hand, and all his servants standing about him. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Saul said to his servants who were standing before him, \uc1\u8220*Listen Benjamites! Will the son of Jesse give you all fields and vineyards? Will he make you all commanders of thousands and commanders of hundreds? {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Is that why all of you have conspired against me, and no one discloses to me that my son has made a covenant with the son of Jesse, and none of you has pity on me or discloses to me that my son has stirred up my servant to be an enemy against me, as is now the case?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Then Doeg the Edomite, who was standing by the servants of Saul, answered, \uc1\u8220*I saw the son of Jesse coming to Nob, to Ahimelech the son of Ahitub. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}He inquired of the {\scaps Lord} for him and gave him provisions and the sword of Goliath the Philistine.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Then the king summoned Ahimelech the priest, the son of Ahitub, and all his father\uc1\u8217*s house, the priests who were in Nob, and they came all of them to the king. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Listen, son of Ahitub!\uc1\u8221* He answered, \uc1\u8220*Here am I, my lord!\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}And Saul said to him, \uc1\u8220*Why have you conspired against me with the son of Jesse, in that you have given him bread and a sword and have inquired of God for him, so that he should rise against me as an enemy, as is now the case?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Then Ahimelech answered the king, \uc1\u8220*But who among all your servants is like David, trusted and the king\uc1\u8217*s son-in-law and captain over your retainers and honored in your household? {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Is this the first time I have inquired of God for him? Of course not! Let not the king impute anything to his servant nor to any one of my clan, for your servant did not know the slightest thing about all this.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}But the king said, \uc1\u8220*You will surely die, Ahimelech, together with all your clan.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}The king said to the runners who stood before him, \uc1\u8220*Turn about and slay the priests of the {\scaps Lord}, for their hand also was with David, and, although they knew that he was fleeing, they did not disclose it to me.\uc1\u8221* But the servants of the king would not put forth their hands to strike down the priests of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Then the king said to Doeg, \uc1\u8220*Turn and strike down the priests.\uc1\u8221* And Doeg the Edomite turned and himself struck down the priests. So he slew on that day eighty-five men who wore the ephod. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}The priestly city Nob he put to the sword, both men and women, children and infants, oxen and donkeys and sheep.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}One of the sons of Ahimelech the son of Ahitub, named Abiathar, escaped and fled to David. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}And Abiathar told David that Saul had slain the priests of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}David said to Abiathar, \uc1\u8220*I knew that day, because Doeg the Edomite was there, that he would surely tell Saul. I myself am guilty of all the lives of your clan. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Remain with me, fear not; for whoever seeks your life must also seek mine. You will be safe with me.\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 23}David was told that Philistines were fighting against Keilah and are robbing the threshing floors. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}David inquired of the {\scaps Lord}, \uc1\u8220*Should I go and attack these Philistines?\uc1\u8221* And the {\scaps Lord} said to David, \uc1\u8220*Go, attack the Philistines, and save Keilah.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}But David\uc1\u8217*s men said to him, \uc1\u8220*Behold we are afraid here in Judah. How much more then if we go to Keilah against the armies of the Philistines?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Then David inquired of the {\scaps Lord} yet again. And the {\scaps Lord} answered him, \uc1\u8220*Arise, go down to Keilah, for I will deliver the Philistines into your hand.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}So David and his men went to Keilah, and fought with the Philistines and drove away their cattle, inflicting heavy losses on them. In this way David delivered the inhabitants of Keilah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}When Abiathar the son of Ahimelech fled to David at Keilah, he came down with the ephod in his hand. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}When Saul was told that David had come to Keilah, Saul said, \uc1\u8220*God has sold him into my hand, for he has entrapped himself in entering into a town that has doors and bars.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 8}And Saul summoned all the people to war, to go down to Keilah, to besiege David and his men. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}When David knew that Saul was devising evil against him, he said to Abiathar the priest, \uc1\u8220*Bring here the ephod.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}And David said, \uc1\u8220*{\scaps Lord}, God of Israel, your servant has surely heard that Saul is seeking to come to Keilah, to destroy the city because of me. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Will Saul come down, as your servant has heard? {\scaps Lord}, God of Israel, I beseech you, tell your servant.\uc1\u8221* And the {\scaps Lord} said, \uc1\u8220*He will come down.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Then David said, \uc1\u8220*Will the men of Keilah deliver me and my men into the hand of Saul?\uc1\u8221* And the {\scaps Lord} said, \uc1\u8220*They will deliver you up.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Then David and his men, who were about six hundred, arose and departed from Keilah, and moving from place to place. When it was reported to Saul that David had escaped from Keilah, he abandoned his expedition. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}So David stayed in the wilderness in the strongholds and remained in the hill-country in the Wilderness of Ziph. Saul sought him continually, but the {\scaps Lord} did not deliver him into his hand.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Now David saw that Saul had come out to seek his life. At that time, he was in the Wilderness of Ziph in Horesha. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}And Jonathan, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, came to David in Horesha and strengthened his hand in God. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}He said to him, \uc1\u8220*Fear not, for the hand of Saul my father will not find you, and you will be king over Israel and I will be next to you. This Saul my father well knows.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}The two of them made a covenant before the {\scaps Lord}, and David stayed in Horesha, and Jonathan returned home.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Then the Ziphites came up to Saul to Gibeah, saying, \uc1\u8220*Is not David hiding himself with us in the strongholds in Horesha, in the hill of Hachilah, which is to the south of Jeshimon? {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Now therefore, O king, according to all your heart\uc1\u8217*s desire, come down, and it will be our part to deliver him into the king\uc1\u8217*s hand.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Then Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Blessed may you be of the {\scaps Lord}, for you have had compassion on me. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Go, I pray, make yet more sure, and know and see the place where his haunt is and who has seen him there, for I am told that he is very cunning. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}See therefore, and gain knowledge of all the lurking-places where he hides, and return to me, with sure information, and I will go with you, and, if he be in the land, I will search him out of all the thousands of Judah.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}So they arose and went to Ziph before Saul. But David and his men were in the Wilderness of Maon, in the Arabah to the south of Jeshimon. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}When Saul and his men went to seek him, David found out and he went down to the rock which is in the Wilderness of Maon. When Saul heard, he pursued after David in the Wilderness of Maon. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Saul went on the one side of the mountain and David and his men on the other side of the mountain. David was anxiously trying to escape from Saul, for Saul and his men were about to surround David and his men, to seize them, {\super\cf2\fs24 27}when a messenger came to Saul, saying, \uc1\u8220*Come quickly, for the Philistines have made a raid upon the land.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 28}So Saul returned from pursuing after David and went against the Philistines. This is why they call that place the Rock of Divisions. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}David went up from there, and stayed in the strongholds of En-gedi. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 24}When Saul returned from following the Philistines, he was told, \uc1\u8220*David is in the Wilderness of En-gedi.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}So Saul took three thousand men chosen from all Israel and went to seek David and his men upon the Wild Goats\uc1\u8217* Crags. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}He came to the sheepfolds by the way, and there was a cave. And Saul went in to relieve himself, while David and his men were staying in the recesses of the cave. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}The men of David said to him, \uc1\u8220*See this is the day of which the {\scaps Lord} said to you, \uc1\u8216*Behold, I give your enemy into your hand and you will do to him as you please.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221* Then David arose, and secretly cut off the skirt of Saul\uc1\u8217*s robe. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}But afterward David was seized with remorse because he had cut off Saul\uc1\u8217*s robe. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}He said to his men, \uc1\u8220*The {\scaps Lord} forbid that I should do this thing to my lord, the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s anointed, to lift my hand against him, since he is the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s anointed.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}So David upbraided his men with these words, and did not permit them to attack Saul. When Saul rose from the cave and went on his way, {\super\cf2\fs24 8}David also rose after him and went from the cave and cried after Saul, saying, \uc1\u8220*My lord the king.\uc1\u8221* When Saul looked behind him, David bowed his face to the earth, and did obeisance. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}And David said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Why did you listen to the words of the men who said, \uc1\u8216*See, David seeks to harm you?\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Today your eyes see that the {\scaps Lord} gave you into my hand in the cave, but I refused to kill you and had pity on you, and I said, \uc1\u8216*I will not lift my hand against my lord, for he is the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s anointed.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Moreover, my father, see the corner of your robe in my hand, for in that I cut off the corner of your robe and did not kill you, know and see that there is neither evil nor guilt on my hands, and I have not sinned against you, though you are aiming to take my life. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}May the {\scaps Lord} judge between me and you, but my hand will not be against you. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}As runs the proverb of the ancients,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
Out of the wicked comes forth wickedness.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
But my hand will not be raised against you. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}After whom is the king of Israel come out? After whom are you pursuing? After a dead dog? After a flea? {\super\cf2\fs24 15}The {\scaps Lord} therefore be judge and decide between me and you and see and plead my cause and obtain justice for me from you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Now when David had finished speaking these words to Saul, Saul said, \uc1\u8220*Is this not your voice, my son David?\uc1\u8221* Then Saul lifted up his voice and wept. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}He said to David, \uc1\u8220*You are more righteous than I, for you have done to me that which is good, while I have done to you that which is evil. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}You have done great good to me in that today, when the {\scaps Lord} had shut me up in your hand, you did not kill me. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}For when a man finds his enemy, does he send him on his way safe and sound? Therefore may the {\scaps Lord} reward you richly for what you have done to me this day. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Now see, I know that you will surely be king, and that through you the kingdom of Israel will be established. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Swear now therefore to me by the {\scaps Lord}, that you will not cut off my descendants after me and that you will not destroy my name from my father\uc1\u8217*s house.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 22}So David took oath to Saul. And Saul went to his home, but David and his men went up to the stronghold. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 25}Samuel died; and all Israel gathered themselves together, and lamented him, and buried him in his house at Ramah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
{\super\cf2\fs24 1}Then David arose and went into the Wilderness of Maon. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}There was a man in Maon, whose business was in Carmel. The man was very rich, and he had three thousand sheep and a thousand goats, and he was shearing his sheep in Carmel. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}The man\uc1\u8217*s name was Nabal, and his wife\uc1\u8217*s name was Abigail. The woman was sensible and beautiful, but the man was rough and ill-mannered. He was a Calebite. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}David heard in the wilderness that Nabal was shearing his sheep. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}So he sent ten young men, saying, \uc1\u8220*Go up to Carmel and enter Nabal\uc1\u8217*s house and greet him in my name, {\super\cf2\fs24 6}and say to him and to his clan, \uc1\u8216*Peace be to you and your house and all that you have. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Now I have heard that you have shearers. Your shepherds were with us, and we did not jeer at them, and nothing of theirs was missing all the while they were in Carmel. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Ask your young men and they will tell you. Therefore let the young men find favor in your eyes, for we have come on a feast day. Give, therefore, whatever you have at hand to your servants and to your son David.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}When David\uc1\u8217*s young men came, they spoke to Nabal in the name of David and waited as directed. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}But Nabal answered David\uc1\u8217*s servants, \uc1\u8220*Who is David? Who is the son of Jesse? Many are the slaves these days who break away, each from his master! {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Should I then take my bread and my water and my meat that I have butchered for my shearers, and give it to men of whom I know not where they came from?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}So David\uc1\u8217*s young men turned back on their way, and came and reported all these words to him. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}And David said to his men, \uc1\u8220*Let every man buckle on his sword.\uc1\u8221* Each man buckled on his sword. And David also buckeled on his sword, and there went up after David about four hundred men while two hundred remained with the baggage.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}But one of the young men had told Abigail, Nabal\uc1\u8217*s wife, \uc1\u8220*David has just sent messengers from the wilderness to salute our master, and he railed at them. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}But the men have been very good to us and we have not been jeered at nor have we missed anything, as long as we went with them, when we were in the fields. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}They were a wall about us both by night and by day all the while we were with them keeping the sheep. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Now therefore know and consider what you will do, for evil is determined against our master and against all his house, for he is such a base scoundrel that no one speak to him.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Then Abigail quickly took two hundred loaves of bread and two skins of wine and five roasted sheep and five mesures of parched grain and a hundred bunches of raisins and two hundred cakes of figs and laid them on donkeys. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}She said to her young men, \uc1\u8220*Go on before me, I am coming after you.\uc1\u8221* But she said nothing about it to her husband Nabal. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Just as she was riding on the donkey and coming down under cover of the mountain, David and his men were also coming down toward her, so that she met them. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Now David had said, \uc1\u8220*Surely for nothing did I guard all that belongs to this fellow in the wilderness, so that nothing of all that belongs to him was missing, for he has returned me evil for good. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}God do whatever he will to David, if I leave by daybreak of all who belong to him as much as a single man.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 23}When Abigail saw David, she alighted quickly from her donkey and fell on her face before David and bowed to the ground. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}She fell at his feet and said, \uc1\u8220*Upon me, my lord, upon me be the guilt. Only let your maid-servant speak in your ears, and heed the words of your servant. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Let not my lord pay any attention to that base scoundrel, Nabal, for as his name is, so is he, \uc1\u8216*Reckless Fool,\uc1\u8217* is his name and folly is his master, but your maid-servant didn\uc1\u8217*t see the young men of my lord, whom you sent.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Now my lord, as the {\scaps Lord} lives and as you live, since the {\scaps Lord} has kept you from committing an act of bloodshed and from delivering yourself by your own hand \uc1\u8211* and may your enemies and those who seek to do evil to my lord be as Nabal \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 27}let this present, which your servant has brought to my lord, be given to the young men who follow my lord {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Forgive, I pray the trespass of your servant, for the {\scaps Lord} will certainly make for my lord a secure house, for my lord is fighting the wars of the {\scaps Lord}, and no evil will be found in you as long as you live. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Should a man rise up to pursue you and to seek your life, the life of my lord will be bound in the bundle of the living in the care of the {\scaps Lord} your God, but the lives of your enemies will he sling out as from the hollow of a sling. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}When the {\scaps Lord} has done to my lord all the good that he has promised you and has made you prince over Israel, {\super\cf2\fs24 31}then this will not be a qualm or a burden on the conscience of my lord, that you have shed blood without cause or that my lord has delivered himself by his own hand. When the {\scaps Lord} gives prosperity to my lord, then remember your servant.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 32}David said to Abigail, \uc1\u8220*Blessed be the {\scaps Lord}, the God of Israel, who sent you this day to meet me, {\super\cf2\fs24 33}and blessed be your discretion, and blessed be you yourself, who have kept me this day from committing an act of bloodshed and from avenging myself by my own hand. {\super\cf2\fs24 34}For as sure as the {\scaps Lord}, the God of Israel, lives, who has kept me from doing you harm, except you had quickly come to meet me, surely there would not have been left to Nabal by daybreak so much as one man.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 35}So David received from her hand that which she had brought him, and to her he said, \uc1\u8220*Go up in peace to your house. See, I have heeded your advice, and granted your request.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 36}But when Abigail came to Nabal, he was just having a banquet in his house, like a king. And Nabal\uc1\u8217*s heart was merry within him, for he was very drunk, so that she did not tell him anything at all until day break. {\super\cf2\fs24 37}But then in the morning when the effects of the wine were gone from Nabal, his wife told him these things, and his heart died within him and he became a stone. {\super\cf2\fs24 38}At the end of about ten days the {\scaps Lord} struck Nabal, so that he died.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 39}Now when David heard that Nabal was dead, he said, \uc1\u8220*Blessed be the {\scaps Lord} who has avenged the case of my insult at the hand of Nabal and has kept back his servant from evil. The evil-doing of Nabal the {\scaps Lord} brought back upon his own head.\uc1\u8221* Then David sent and wooed Abigail to take her to him to be his wife.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 40}When the servants of David came to Abigail at Carmel and said to her, \uc1\u8220*David has sent us to you to take you to him to be his wife,\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 41}She rose and bowed with her face to the earth and said, \uc1\u8220*See, your slave is willing to be a servant to wash the feet of my lord\uc1\u8217*s servants.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 42}Abigail quickly arose and mounted an donkey, and five maids followed as servants. So she accompanied the messengers of David and became his wife.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 43}David also took Ahinoam of Jezreel, and they both became his wives. {\super\cf2\fs24 44}But Saul had given Michal his daughter, David\uc1\u8217*s wife, to Palti the son of Laish to Gallim. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 26}Then the Ziphites came to Saul at Gibeah, saying, \uc1\u8220*David is hiding in the hill of Hachilah, which is east of the desert.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Accordingly Saul arose, and went down to the Wilderness of Ziph, with three thousand men of Israel, to seek David in the Wilderness of Ziph. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Saul encamped beside the road on the hill of Hachilah overlooking Jeshimon. But David remained in the wilderness. When he saw that Saul was pursuing him into the wilderness, {\super\cf2\fs24 4}David sent out spies and learned that Saul had come there after him, {\super\cf2\fs24 5}so he arose and came to the place where Saul had encamped. And David saw the place where Saul lay, with Abner the son of Ner, the commander of his army. Saul lay within the barricade, and the people were encamped around about him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Then David spoke to Ahimelech the Hittite and to Abishai the son Zeruiah, Joab\uc1\u8217*s brother, saying, \uc1\u8220*Who will go down with me into the camp to Saul?\uc1\u8221* And Abishai said, \uc1\u8220*I will go down with you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}So David and Abishai went to the army by night. Saul was lying there asleep within the barricade, with his spear stuck into the earth at his head, with Abner and the people lying around about him. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Abishai said to David, \uc1\u8220*God has delivered your enemy into your hand today. Now therefore let me strike him with his spear to the earth at one stroke, and I will not need to strike him twice!\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}But David said to Abishai, \uc1\u8220*Do not destroy him, for who can lay his hand upon the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s anointed and be innocent?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}David said, \uc1\u8220*As the {\scaps Lord} lives, either the {\scaps Lord} will strike him, or his day will come to die, or he will go down into battle and be destroyed. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}The {\scaps Lord} forbid that I should lift my hand against the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s anointed, but now take the spear that is at his head and the jug of water and let us go.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}So David took the spear and the jug of water from Saul\uc1\u8217*s head and they departed. No man saw it of knew it neither did any awake, for they were all asleep because a deep sleep from the {\scaps Lord} had fallen upon them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Then David went over to the other side and stood on the top of a mountain at a distance, a great space being between them. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}And David cried to the army and to Abner, the son of Ner, \uc1\u8220*Do you make no answer Abner?\uc1\u8221* Then Abner answered, \uc1\u8220*Who are you that calls to the king?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}And David said to Abner, \uc1\u8220*Are you not a man? Who is like you in Israel? Why then have you not kept guard over your lord the king? For one of the people came to destroy your lord. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}This that you have done is not good. As the {\scaps Lord} lives, you are deserving death, because you have not kept watch over your lord, the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s anointed. Now see where the king\uc1\u8217*s spear is and the jug of water that was at his head.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Then Saul recognized David\uc1\u8217*s voice and said, \uc1\u8220*Is this your voice, my son David?\uc1\u8221* And David said, \uc1\u8220*It is my voice, my lord the king.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 18}He said, \uc1\u8220*Why is my lord pursuing his servant? For what have I done? Or of what kind of evil have I been guilty? {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Now therefore let my lord the king hear the words of his servant. If the {\scaps Lord} has stirred you up against me, let him accept an offering, but if it was men, cursed be they before the {\scaps Lord}, for they have driven me out today, so that I have no part in the inheritance of the {\scaps Lord}, saying, \uc1\u8216*Go serve other gods.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Now therefore, may my blood not fall to the earth far away from the presence of the {\scaps Lord}, for the king of Israel has come out to look for a flea, as one hunts a partridge on the mountains.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Then Saul said, \uc1\u8220*I have done wrong. Return, my son David, for I will do you no more harm, because my life was regarded as sacred by you today. I have acted foolishly and have erred exceedingly.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 22}And David answered, \uc1\u8220*There is the king\uc1\u8217*s spear! Let one of the young men come over and take it. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}And the {\scaps Lord} will reward each man\uc1\u8217*s righteousness and fidelity, for the {\scaps Lord} delivered you into my hand today, but I would not raise my hand against the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*a anointed. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Just as your life was today of great value in my sight, so may my life be of great value in the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s sight, and let him deliver me out of all affliction.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Then Saul said to David, \uc1\u8220*Be blessed, my son David; you will do great things and will surely succeed!\uc1\u8221* So David went his way, but Saul returned to his place. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 David among the Philistines

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 27}Then David said to himself, \uc1\u8220*I will be destroyed some day by the hand of Saul. There is nothing better for me than that I should escape into the land of the Philistines. Then Saul will despair of seeking me any longer in all the territory of Israel, and I will escape from his hand.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}So David set out, together with the six hundred men who were with him, to Achish the son of Maoch, king of Gath. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}David stayed with Achish at Gath, together with his men, each with his household and David with his two wives, Ahinoam the Jezreelite and Abigail the Carmelite, Nabal\uc1\u8217*s widow. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}When Saul was informed that David had fled to Gath, he sought him no more.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}David Said to Achish, \uc1\u8220*If now I have found favor in your sight, let a place in one of the towns in the open country be given me, that I may live there, for why should your servant live in the royal city with you?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 6}So Achish gave him Ziklag at that time, therefore Ziklag belongs to the kings of Judah to this day. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The length of the time that David lived in the open country of the Philistines was a year and four months.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}David and his men went up, and made a raid upon the Geshurites, the Girzites, and the Amalekites, for these tribes live in the land which extends from Telem as far as Shur, all the way down to Egypt. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}As often as David struck the land, he did not leave alive man or woman, but taking the sheep, the oxen, the asses, the camels, and the clothing, he returned and came to Achish. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}When Achish said, \uc1\u8220*Where have you made a raid today?\uc1\u8221* David answered, \uc1\u8220*Against the Negreb of Judah\uc1\u8221*, or \uc1\u8220*against the Negreb of the Jerahmeelites\uc1\u8221*, or \uc1\u8220*against the Negreb of the Kenites.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}But David never left alive man or woman, to bring them to Gath, for he thought, \uc1\u8220*They might give information against us and say, \uc1\u8216*David has done this, or that.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221* Such was his custom all the while he lived in the open country of the Philistines. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}And Achish trusted David, thinking, \uc1\u8220*He has brought himself into ill odor with his people Israel, therefore he will be my servant forever.\uc1\u8221* 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 28}Now in those days the Philistines assembled their forces to make a campaign against Israel. Achish said to David, \uc1\u8220*You know thqt you must, together with your men,  go with me along with the forces.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}David said to Achish, \uc1\u8220*Good, you will now know what your servant can do.\uc1\u8221* And Achish said to David, \uc1\u8220*I will make you my bodyguard from this time on.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Now Samuel had died and all Israel had lamented for him and buried him in Ramah, his own city. And Saul had banished the mediums and magicians out of the land. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}When the Philistines assembled and came and encamped in Shunem, Saul assembled all Israel, and they encamped in Gilboa. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}When Saul saw the army of the Philistines, he was afraid and his heart was filled with apprehension. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Saul inquired of the {\scaps Lord}, but the {\scaps Lord} did not answer him either by dreams or by Urim or by prophets. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Then Saul said to his servants, \uc1\u8220*Find for me a woman who is a medium so that I may go to her and inquire through her.\uc1\u8221* His servants said to him, \uc1\u8220*Behold, there is a medium at Endor.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}So Saul disguised himself and put on other clothes and went, taking two men with him, and they came to the woman by night. He said, \uc1\u8220*Tell my future by consulting the dead, call up for me the one whom I name to you.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}The woman said to him, Surely you know what Saul has done, how he has banished the mediums and the magicians from the land. Why then are you laying a snare for my life, to put me to death?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}And Saul swore to her by the {\scaps Lord}, saying, \uc1\u8220*As the {\scaps Lord} lives, no guilt will come upon you for this.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Then the woman said, \uc1\u8220*Whom should I bring up to you?\uc1\u8221* He said, \uc1\u8220*Bring up Samuel.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 12}When the woman saw Samuel, she screamed. The woman said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Why have you deceived me, for you are Saul?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 13}The king said to her, \uc1\u8220*Do not be afraid! What do you see?\uc1\u8221* The woman said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*I see a god coming up out of the earth.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 14}He said to her, \uc1\u8220*What is his appearance?\uc1\u8221* She said, \uc1\u8220*An old man is coming up, and he is wrapped in a robe.\uc1\u8221* Then Saul knew that it was Samuel, and he bowed with his face to the earth in respect.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Samuel said to Saul, \uc1\u8220*Why have you disturbed me by bringing me up?\uc1\u8221* And Saul answered, \uc1\u8220*I am in great trouble, for the Philistines are making war against me and God has turned from me and answers me no more, either by prophets or by dreams; so I have called you to tell me what I should do.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}And Samuel said, \uc1\u8220*Why do you ask of me when the {\scaps Lord} has turned from you and become your adversary? {\super\cf2\fs24 17}The {\scaps Lord} has done to you as he declared by me, and the {\scaps Lord} has torn the kingdom out of your hand, and given it to your neighbor, David. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Because you did not heed the voice of the {\scaps Lord}, and did not execute his fierce wrath upon Amalek, the {\scaps Lord} has done this thing to you today. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}The {\scaps Lord} will deliver Israel into the power of the Philistines. Tomorrow you and your sons will be with me, and the {\scaps Lord} will deliver the army of Israel into the power of the Philistines.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Then Saul fell at once at full length upon the earth and was greatly afraid, because of the words of Samuel, and he had no strength in him, for he had not eaten bread during all the day and all the night. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}When the woman came to Saul and saw that he was greatly troubled, she said to him, \uc1\u8220*Your servant has heeded your voice, and I have taken my life in my hand and have listened to your words which you spoke to me. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Now therefore, listen also to the advice of your servant and let me set before you a morsel of meat, and eat that you may have strength when you go on your way.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 23}But he refused, and said, \uc1\u8220*I will not eat.\uc1\u8221* But his servants, together with the woman urged him, until he listened to their advice. So he rose from the earth and sat upon the couch. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}The woman had a fatted calf in the house, and she quickly killed it, and took flour and kneaded it and baked from it unleavened bread. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}She set it before Saul and his servants and they ate. Then they rose and went away that night. 
